[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ It was 1766 when Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue  (Italy, 1715-1780)  published his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi. In it one finds some general words about the game of chess, tips on how to play the game well, followed by hundreds of pages filled with variations. It all happens on page 252 though. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ After the introductory moves, he continues:  ‘the knight of the king, moves to the 2nd square of the king’ , and thus the Cozio-variation was born! }
3... Nge7
{ Black chooses an unusual way of developing the king’s knight, but it is certainly not without logic. If White is ever to take on c6, we are now ready to recapture with the knight. Having the knight on e7 also means the e5-pawn is safely defended in the foreseeable future. Last but not least, Black's 3rd move is flexible, giving Black the option to install the knight on g6 later on, or to play ...g7-g6 instead and fianchetto the bishop. We will be making use of both setups throughout this course.   There are also certain practical upsides to  3...Nge7  . The big alternatives, Morphy’s  3...a6  and the infamous Berlin  3...Nf6  , have over time exploded in terms of opening theory. The main downside, besides blocking the bishop on  f8  , is that  3...Nge7  does not, for now, ask White any questions, giving the opponent a wide range of setups to choose from.  In this course, I will be showing many brand new directions where there are zero practical tests to be found. That means that by going  3...Nge7  we lower the burden on our memory and have a good chance of surprising our opponents.  The reputation of the Cozio isn’t that great and top players have mostly seen it as a weapon they occasionally use in rapid/blitz games. I was initially surprised as well to find out that the line holds up against modern-day scrutiny. Using the latest engines, I found that many old perceptions are up for reappraisal. I then decided the Cozio would be a great topic to do a course on for Chessable.  Just before publishing this course, I had a chance to play the line myself in the German Bundesliga. It became a rather surreal experience. Having caught my opponent in a new branch I present in chapter 6, I got a winning position as early as move 8, only to mix up the move order and be actually lost on move 9!  Some of the lines really require the move trainer to make sure we are aware of all the details. Once we are though, I believe the Cozio can prove a very valuable @@StartBracket@@surprise@@EndBracket@@ weapon!    Erwin l’Ami  December 2020 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Cozio Defence - Reference"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ This Reference serves to show the big picture of our Cozio repertoire. Without going in too much detail, I want to illustrate what this variation is about. After Black's third move, White has four serious replies: }
4. Nc3
{ The big test!   4.c3  A very logical move, White's aim is to set up a big centre with d2-d4 next. We react with an innovation by the first World Champion, Wilhelm Steinitz.  4...d5!  5.Nxe5  The only serious reply.  5...dxe4  6.Qe2  The critical test, introduced by another World Champion: Bobby Fischer!   6.Qa4  was played in Fraser-Steinitz, which the latter won convincingly. You can find this game, in the chapter onModel Games.  6...Be6!  And this move brings us back to modern times. After Fischer introduced 6.Qe2 it was thought for a long time that the Cozio was unplayable. Until 2008, when Indian GM Abhijeet Gupta introduced the text move. The point is that  7.Qxe4  Bd5!  wins back the pawn, and the other direction,  6...Be6!  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.Ba6  Qd7  9.O-O  Ng6!  is a very strong pawn sacrifice that I discovered while preparing the course. As it stands now, 4.c3 is not the best way of testing the Cozio.   4.d4  This move is not very popular but we should be well aware of it. It contains a deep positional trap.  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  . Our first instinct may be to play  5...g6  but now  6.Nxc6!  Nxc6   6...bxc6  7.Qd4!  forces ...Rg8 after which the king on e8 has a tough time getting out of the centre.  7.Bd2!  Bg7  8.Bc3  immediately trades the strong bishop on g7 and leaves White with a pleasant space advantage.   Instead of 5...g6, we have @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/2n5/1B6/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nxd4  6.Qxd4  Nc6  7.Qe3  Be7  We continue normal development. The only thing we have to think about is how to react to the incoming Nb1-c3-d5.  8.Nc3  O-O  9.O-O  Re8!  The final point to make. Black postpones ...d7-d6 so that after  10.Nd5  there is  10...Nb4!  exchanging the strong knight on d5. More details in thesecond chapter.   4.O-O  This is the most popular move in the position and for obvious reasons. What could be more normal than to castle?  4...g6  The only line where I recommend a setup connected to the move ...g7-g6.  5.c3  a6  It is useful to give the bishop a push before developing the bishop to g7. Why that's the case will shortly become clear!  6.Ba4  Bg7  7.d4  exd4  8.cxd4  b5  . The way this line used to be played, with Black going ...d7-d5 without including ...a6-b5, White would be able to take on  c6  later on and double Black's pawn. That has now been averted. There is much more to say about this position, and inChapter 4 we certainly will, but for now, suffice to say that  9.Bb3  is an important move, as well as  9.Bc2  d5  10.exd5  Nb4  11.Bb3  Nbxd5  gives Black equal chances. }
4... Ng6
{ We slightly break the rules by making another move with our knight. This line is relatively unexplored and most of the analysis I will present is original.   4...g6  cannot be recommended here, as  5.d4  exd4  6.Nxd4  Bg7  7.Be3  O-O  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.Ba4  gives White a big advantage. For instance  9...d5  10.Bc5!  and Black has a hard time finding a move. }
5. d4
{ The most obvious reply. The position resembles a strange mixture of the Ruy Lopez and Scotch Four Knights.   5.h4  is the most testing move, immediately going after our knight. I'm quite proud of the solution I found here:  5...Nd4  6.Bc4  h5!  Brand new and containing a major trap.  7.Ng5  isn't f7 hanging now?  7...d5!  It turns out the complications after 7...d5 are perfectly fine for Black! Obviously, this needs to be analyzed in great detail and we will do so in the course. }
5... exd4 6. Nxd4 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 c6
{ Kicking away the bishop and preparing ...Qd8-b6. } 8. Be2 Qb6
{ Exchanging queens leads to a fine endgame for Black, so White will have to move the queen. As we will see in the final chapter, we then continue ...Bf8-e7, ...O-O etc, with an approximately equal game.   Having gotten acquainted with the Cozio, I now invite the reader to start with the entrée. }
*

