{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. c4 { Positionally not very sound. } 4... Ng6 5. O-O
{ 5.Nc3  Nd4!?  Grabbing the initiative. Black prepares c7-c6 and note that  6.Nxd4  exd4  7.Ne2  d3!  8.Ng3  c6  9.Ba4  h5!  is already terrible for White. The pawn on d3 ties White's position and the threat of ...h5-h4 is already very real.   5.d4  Not very consistent, mixing up various plans.  5...exd4  6.Nxd4  Bb4+  Simplest, but no doubt Black has other options too.  7.Nc3  O-O  We are ready to take on d4 and follow up with ...d7-d6, bringing the c8-bishop into the game. }
5... Bc5
{ Getting a firm grip over the d4-square. Black is fully in control and will follow up with ...O-O, ...Nc6-d4, ...d7-d6 @@StartBracket@@in random order@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: Off the Beaten Track - Sidelines"]
[Black "Sidelines 4.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. Bc4
{ I give this an interesting mark as I really like the originality. White simply 'switches' openings and starts playing an Italian where the claim is that the knight on e7 is misplaced. Original it surely is, but dangerous it is not. }
4... d5
{ The most principled reply. White has wasted time and we use it to open up the centre.   4...g6  5.Ng5  d5  is a weird version of the Two Knights Defence @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Nf6  4.Ng5  d5  (where the knight is on f6, instead of e7!)  and I would prefer to avoid it.   4...Ng6  though, is playable as well. }
5. exd5 Nxd5
{ A very confusing position! It is as if @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  got met with  3...Nf6  & ...d7-d5 to reach the position on the board after 4.exd5 Nxd5. }
6. O-O Be7 { Essentially a pawn sacrifice. } 7. Re1 Bg4
{ Inviting White to grab the e5-pawn by provoking significant weaknesses on the kingside. }
8. h3 { 8.Nc3  Nxc3  9.bxc3  O-O  makes life  (too)  easy for Black. } 8... Bh5
9. g4 Bg6 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5
{ The critical position. It turns out White's king is too compromised to be able to really enjoy the extra pawn. }
11... Nb6 12. Bb3 O-O
{ Black follows up with ...Kh8! and ...f7-f5, and the bishop on e7 will likely land on d6. It will be hard for White to stop Black's initiative from taking shape. }
*

