{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. d3 { A timid response, to which we reply in usual fashion. } 4... Ng6
{ 4...g6  isn't bad either, but gives White the chance to execute the main idea behind 4.d3 →  5.h4!?  The standard move in these modern times! While it would be a gross exaggeration to say White is better here, the position can get sharp fast. One sample line is  5...h6   5...Bg7  6.h5  is annoying, and so is   5...h5  which weakens our dark squares.  6.Nc3  Bg7  And I would certainly recommend playing this way for Black, if not for  7.h5  g5  8.Nxg5!?  hxg5  9.Bxg5  which is a very dangerous piece sacrifice. The following line illustrates the dangers:  9...f6  10.h6  fxg5  11.Qh5+  Kf8  12.Qf3+  Ke8  13.hxg7!!  Rxh1+  14.Kd2  and wins, as  14...Rxa1  15.Qf8#  is mate.   I think our go-to move  4...Ng6  is much easier. }
5. O-O { Gives Black a wide range of options. } 5... Be7 6. Nc3 O-O
{ I like the straightforwardness of Black's play. Next up is ...d7-d6 and ...f7-f5. }
7. Nd5 { Going for the bishop on e7, but Black can continue undisturbed. } 7...
d6
{ Perfectly reasonable is  7...a6  8.Ba4  b5  9.Bb3  Na5  so that after  10.Nxe7+  Qxe7  11.Bg5  Qe8  Black will take on b3 next with an equal game. }
8. Nxe7+ Qxe7
{ An exchange we generally welcome. Black will play ...f7-f5 next and is quite happy to get rid of the passive bishop on e7. }
