{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. Bxc6
{ Perhaps the most illogical move in the position, as Black's previous move prepares for this exchange. }
4... dxc6
{ A surprising recapture perhaps, but play now resembles an Exchange Spanish @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Bxc6  dxc6  where Black has played ...Ng8-e7 instead of ...a7-a6. It is clear that the former is a much more useful move.   4...Nxc6  5.Nc3  Bc5  is of course comfortable too, but the text move is more ambitious. Black intends to play ...c6-c5 and ...Ne7-c6. }
5. O-O
{ Threatening to take on e5 and forcing Black to move away from the plan connected to c6-c5 and Ne7-c6.   Immediately capturing the pawn with  5.Nxe5  runs into  5...Qd4!  when Black is in excellent shape. }
5... Ng6
{ The knight is well placed on g6. It not only covers e5, but by moving it from e7, Black is now also ready to bring the f8-bishop into the game. We could end the line here, concluding Black has excellent play, but I think it is useful to look at two typical pawn moves for White. }
6. d3 { Gives Black a free hand. } 6... c5
{ Making sure White will never get the d3-d4 break in. } 7. Be3 Be7 8. Nc3 Be6
{ Black is already slightly better. } *

