{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. d4 { Not a very popular move but one that contains a deep positional trap. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ This has my preference and feels very natural. As the knights get exchanged, the e7-knight can jump to c6 with tempo.   The thing I dislike about  5...g6  is the capture  6.Nxc6!?  which is now well-timed and the trap I was referring to earlier.   6.Nc3  Bg7  7.Be3  O-O  is OK for Black.  6...Nxc6  The only move, as   6...bxc6  7.Qd4!  is very strong, forcing the ugly  7...Rg8  meaning Black won't castle any time soon.   Instead,  6...dxc6  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.Bc4  is an ugly endgame, which leaves the recapture with the knight.  7.Bd2  Ready to exchange Black's 'Dragon' bishop on  g7  . Now I think  7...Bg7  8.Bc3  O-O  9.Bxg7  Kxg7  10.Nc3  is very pleasant for White. The exchanges on  c6  and  g7  have removed any dynamic options Black normally has. The ...d7-d5 break for instance, won't happen any time soon. I don't think Black is much worse here but I feel White has the type of risk-free and slightly better position I would prefer to avoid. }
6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qe3 { The most popular move. } 7... Be7
{ Typical is  7...Bb4+  with the idea to provoke  8.c3  before dropping back with  8...Be7  and claim that a weakness has been created. Stronger is  8.Nc3  O-O  9.Bd2!  preparing to castle on the opposite side of the board.   Also fine is  9.O-O  d6  10.Nd5  with a slightly better game, but following  10...Bc5  11.Qg3  Kh8  12.Bd2  Nd4  13.Bd3  c6  14.Nf4  Ne6  15.Bc3  Qg5  16.Qxg5  Nxg5  an endgame was reached that Black eventually held in Hort-Larsen, Bristol rapid 1979.  9...d6  10.O-O-O  is a very dangerous position for Black. White's play is very straightforward as pawns will be pushed on the kingside with f2-f4, g2-g4 etc. }
8. Nc3 { 8.O-O  O-O  9.Nc3  transposes. } 8... O-O 9. Nd5 Nb4
{ Equalizes on the spot. } 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7
{ White has a tough time covering all the weaknesses. } 11. Ba4
{ Looks artificial and Black has an easy response. } 11... b5
{ 11...Re8  12.f3  d5!?  13.O-O  b5  is fine too, as after  14.Bb3  c5  White has to start thinking of equalizing with, for example  15.a3  c4  16.axb4  cxb3  17.Qxb3  dxe4  18.fxe4  when  18...Be6  leaves engines circling around 0.00 and the position is indeed around equal. }
12. Bb3 c5 { Threatening ...c5-c4, which does the job. } *

