{ This has my preference and feels very natural. As the knights get exchanged, the e7-knight can jump to c6 with tempo.   The thing I dislike about  5...g6  is the capture  6.Nxc6!?  which is now well-timed and the trap I was referring to earlier.   6.Nc3  Bg7  7.Be3  O-O  is OK for Black.  6...Nxc6  The only move, as   6...bxc6  7.Qd4!  is very strong, forcing the ugly  7...Rg8  meaning Black won't castle any time soon.   Instead,  6...dxc6  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.Bc4  is an ugly endgame, which leaves the recapture with the knight.  7.Bd2  Ready to exchange Black's 'Dragon' bishop on  g7  . Now I think  7...Bg7  8.Bc3  O-O  9.Bxg7  Kxg7  10.Nc3  is very pleasant for White. The exchanges on  c6  and  g7  have removed any dynamic options Black normally has. The ...d7-d5 break for instance, won't happen any time soon. I don't think Black is much worse here but I feel White has the type of risk-free and slightly better position I would prefer to avoid. }
6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qe3 { The most popular move. } 7... Be7
{ Typical is  7...Bb4+  with the idea to provoke  8.c3  before dropping back with  8...Be7  and claim that a weakness has been created. Stronger is  8.Nc3  O-O  9.Bd2!  preparing to castle on the opposite side of the board.   Also fine is  9.O-O  d6  10.Nd5  with a slightly better game, but following  10...Bc5  11.Qg3  Kh8  12.Bd2  Nd4  13.Bd3  c6  14.Nf4  Ne6  15.Bc3  Qg5  16.Qxg5  Nxg5  an endgame was reached that Black eventually held in Hort-Larsen, Bristol rapid 1979.  9...d6  10.O-O-O  is a very dangerous position for Black. White's play is very straightforward as pawns will be pushed on the kingside with f2-f4, g2-g4 etc. }
8. Nc3 { 8.O-O  O-O  9.Nc3  transposes. } 8... O-O 9. O-O Re8
{ An important move. By not yet touching the d7-pawn Black retains more flexibility.   The alternatives just show how subtle this position is.  9...d6  10.Nd5  gave White an easy edge in Stripunsky-Benjamin, New York 2000.   And  9...Bf6  10.Nd5  is worse too, as the bishop on f6 can not be preserved. }
10. Nd5 Nb4
{ The most sensible option, but it was hard for me to choose between this one and 10...Bd6.   The downside of  10...Bd6  is that it looks very odd, but that's about the only issue. And in these days of engines, if something works, it works! Black intends to play ...Nc6-e7, ...c7-c6, drop the bishop back to c7 and follow up with ...d7-d5. Let's see how that looks in reality.  11.f4  The most obvious move, and the best illustration of how Black should react.   11.Bd2  Ne7  12.Nf4   12.Nc3  c6  13.Bd3  Bc7  preparing ...d7-d5, equalizes swiftly.  12...Ng6   Also  12...Be5  13.Nd3  Nf5!  works, as  14.exf5  Bxh2+  15.Kxh2  Rxe3  16.Bxe3  a6!  17.Ba4  Qh4+!  wins back the material with interest!  13.Nxg6  hxg6  the position is around equal. Plans are ...b7-b6/Bc8-b7, or the usual ...c7-c6 followed by moving the bishop on d6 and pushing ...d7-d5.  11...Ne7  12.Nc3  c6  13.Bd3  Bc7!  threatening to win a queen with ...Bc7-b6, as well as making way for the freeing advance ...d7-d5. Following  14.Kh1  d5  Black has completely freed the position and equalized comfortably.  I hope you see my dilemma now as both the text move and 10...Bd6 seem to be perfectly in order. I feel 10...Nb4 is a bit more natural but do make your own pick! }
11. Nxe7+
{ The principled option, White takes the bishop pair.   Not  11.Nxb4  Bxb4  12.Qf3  Qe7  13.Bc4  d6  where ...Bc8-e6 next will equalize comfortably. Even the inclusion  14.Bg5  Qf8  won't change that. }
11... Qxe7
{ We have seen this situation before, White lacks the time to properly stabilize in order to enjoy the bishop pair. }
12. Qb3 Qc5
{ Please do avoid the beautiful trap  12...Qxe4  13.Bd2!  Nxc2  14.Qc3!!  which threatens Bb5-d3, while  14...Nxa1  15.Re1  is also winning. An idea which is very hard to spot and even easier to miss! }
13. Bc4 { Now we force things. } 13... d5 14. Bxd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 c6
{ Equalizes. } 16. dxc6 Qxc6 17. Be3 Bf5
{ Black balanced the game because of the opposite-colored bishops and the fact that White has trouble holding on to the extra pawn. }
18. c3
{ 18.Rac1  Re6  and ...Rae8, ...h5-h4 etc next, is liked by the engines. }
18... Be4 19. f3 Bd5 { A nasty trap. } *

