[Result "*"]

{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. c3
{ A very sensible reply - White intends to set up a big centre with d2-d4. It, however, allows Black to equalize on the spot. }
4... d5
{ Steinitz's move, which he introduced in 1867. It was thought to be dubious for a while, afterFischer won a good game with White in 1971, but later updates have placed it back in the limelight. }
5. Nxe5 { The only serious reply. } 5... dxe4 6. Nxc6
{ It's illogical to exchange the strong knight on e5 unprovoked. } 6... Nxc6
{ 6...bxc6!?  is a more active continuation. After  7.Ba4  the important point is  7...Ba6!  keeping the king in the centre.   But White has another option after  6...bxc6!?  , where I feel that  7.Bc4  Nd5  8.d3  exd3  9.O-O  Bc5  10.Qxd3  O-O  11.Nd2  gives White some  (small)  chances to play for an advantage, given the pawn structure.  White refrains from @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/p1p2ppp/2p5/3n4/2B1p3/2P5/PP1P1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.O-O  due to  8...Nb6!  9.Bb3  Ba6!  and if  9.Be2  Bf5  keeps good control over the position by preventing White from playing d2-d4. }
7. O-O Bd6 { 7...Bf5  looks healthy too. } 8. Re1 O-O
{ This pawn sacrifice is very promising. } 9. Rxe4 f5
{ 9...Qg5  is an option too, there are various ways of conducting the attack here. }
10. Re1 Qh4
{ 10...Ne5  is very sensible as well, bringing the knight over to g4 to assist in the attack. }
11. h3 f4 { Already threatens to take on h3 with the bishop. } 12. Qf3
{ Stopping the Bxh3 threat doesn't help much. } 12... g5
{ Pushing the g-pawn is simplest.   But  12...Ne5  13.Rxe5  Bxe5  14.Qd5+  Kh8  15.Qxe5  is also very good for Black, as the line continues with  15...Bxh3!  16.gxh3  Qxh3  when ...Rf8-f5 next guarantees a mating attack. }
13. Bxc6
{ Also after  13.d4  g4  14.Qd5+  Kh8  , Black's attack is unstoppable. } 13...
bxc6 14. Qxc6 g4 { Not wasting any time! It's all about the king on g1. } 15.
Qxa8 gxh3 16. Qf3 Kh8 { With decisive threats along the g-file. } *

