{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. c3
{ A very sensible reply - White intends to set up a big centre with d2-d4. It, however, allows Black to equalize on the spot. }
4... d5
{ Steinitz's move, which he introduced in 1867. It was thought to be dubious for a while, afterFischer won a good game with White in 1971, but later updates have placed it back in the limelight. }
5. Nxe5 { The only serious reply. } 5... dxe4 6. Qe2
{ Fischer's move, which placed a huge dark cloud over the entire Cozio Defence for a while. }
6... Be6
{ A relatively recent discovery by Indian grandmaster Abhijeet Gupta.   Fischer's idea becomes apparent after  6...Qd5  7.Nxc6  Nxc6  when White used the queen on e2 to liberate his position with  8.d4!  and won swiftly:  8...Bf5  9.Nd2  O-O-O  10.O-O  Bg6  11.Nb3  f5  12.Be3  Qf7  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.Qa6+  Kd7  15.Na5  Qe6  16.c4  Be7  17.Rfd1  Black played a few more moves but could have safely resigned in Fischer-Shipman, New York 1971.   Leela suggests that  6...Bf5  is playable, but I am reluctant to recommend the position after  7.O-O  Qd6  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.Ba6  which looks worse to me, or at the very least hard to play for Black. }
7. Qxe4
{ It is important to start by answering what happens if White takes the pawn. }
7... Bd5 { White is forced to give back the pawn. } 8. Qe2 Bxg2 9. Rg1 a6
{ A good intermediate move!   9...Bd5  10.d4  f6  is not that clear, but is certainly a better version of things for White.  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Bd3  Qd6  13.Rg3  saw White eventually prevailing in Kucherov-Velker, Correspondence Chess 2018. }
10. Ba4
{ Exchanging all the pieces with  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.Bxc6+  bxc6  is fine for Black as White has no pieces in the game. For instance  12.d4  Qd6  13.Rg3  f6  preparing Ke8-f7, where the king is very well placed. }
10... Bd5 11. c4 Be6
{ An attempt to play for an advantage.   Here Ivan Sokolov's suggestion, The Ruy Lopez Revisited p.148, of  11...b5  is very possible too, as  12.Nxc6  Bxc6  13.cxb5  axb5  14.Bxb5  Bxb5  15.Qxb5+  c6  16.Qc4  Qc7  gives Black great play for the pawn. By defending  c6  and attacking  h2  , Black gains time to complete development with ...Ne7-g6 and ...Bf8-e7 before castling. White's position lacks cohesion.   12.cxd5  Qxd5  13.Nxc6  Qxc6!  wins back the material under good circumstances, and   12.cxb5  Nxe5  13.Qxe5  axb5  14.Bxb5+  c6  is great for Black too. }
12. Nc3 g6
{ If Black gets to play Bf8-g7 and O-O, White will be in positional trouble. }
13. Qe4 Bg7 { Sacrificing a pawn for speedy development. } 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15.
Bxc6+ Nxc6 16. Qxc6+ Bd7 17. Qe4+ Kf8
{ ...Bd7-f5 comes next and Black is for choice. } *

