6... Be6
{ A relatively recent discovery by Indian grandmaster Abhijeet Gupta.   Fischer's idea becomes apparent after  6...Qd5  7.Nxc6  Nxc6  when White used the queen on e2 to liberate his position with  8.d4!  and won swiftly:  8...Bf5  9.Nd2  O-O-O  10.O-O  Bg6  11.Nb3  f5  12.Be3  Qf7  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.Qa6+  Kd7  15.Na5  Qe6  16.c4  Be7  17.Rfd1  Black played a few more moves but could have safely resigned in Fischer-Shipman, New York 1971.   Leela suggests that  6...Bf5  is playable, but I am reluctant to recommend the position after  7.O-O  Qd6  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.Ba6  which looks worse to me, or at the very least hard to play for Black. }
7. d4 { Not too interesting. } 7... exd3 8. Nxd3 Ng6 9. O-O Bd6 10. f4
{ Deviating from the Caruana-Sokolov game, mentioned in the previous trainable. }
10... Qe7
{ If we are playing for the beauty prize,  10...O-O  11.f5  a6  12.Bxc6  Bc4!!  is another amazing way to play.  13.fxg6  Bxd3  14.Qxd3  Bxh2+!  is one of the ideas.  The lines continue @@StartFEN@@r2q1rk1/1pp2ppp/p1Bb2n1/5P2/2b5/2PN4/PP2Q1PP/RNB2RK1 w - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Be4  Ne5  14.Rd1  Nxd3  15.Bxd3  Re8  16.Be3  Qh4  17.Bxc4  Qxh2+  18.Kf1  Qh1+  19.Kf2  Qh4+  and as usual, the wild lines end in perpetual check... }
11. Qf2
{ 11.f5  is no problem and can be answered with  11...Bxf5  12.Qxe7+  Ngxe7  ,  protecting the bishop on f5. }
11... O-O 12. f5 Bd5 13. fxg6
{ 13.Re1  Qh4!  14.g3  Qg4  is also not a picnic for White, with ...Ng6-h4 coming and  15.fxg6  fxg6  16.Qe2  Rae8  17.Qxe8  Qf3  not being an option. }
13... fxg6 14. Bf4
{ Not much better is  14.Qe1  Rxf1+  15.Kxf1  Rf8+  16.Kg1  Bc5+  17.Kh1  Qe4!  when White will get mated in short order. }
14... Rxf4 { Followed by ...Bd6-c5, wins the house. } *

