{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. c3
{ A very sensible reply - White intends to set up a big centre with d2-d4. It, however, allows Black to equalize on the spot. }
4... d5
{ Steinitz's move, which he introduced in 1867. It was thought to be dubious for a while, afterFischer won a good game with White in 1971, but later updates have placed it back in the limelight. }
5. Nxe5 { The only serious reply. } 5... dxe4 6. Qe2
{ Fischer's move, which placed a huge dark cloud over the entire Cozio Defence for a while. }
6... Be6
{ A relatively recent discovery by Indian grandmaster Abhijeet Gupta.   Fischer's idea becomes apparent after  6...Qd5  7.Nxc6  Nxc6  when White used the queen on e2 to liberate his position with  8.d4!  and won swiftly:  8...Bf5  9.Nd2  O-O-O  10.O-O  Bg6  11.Nb3  f5  12.Be3  Qf7  13.Bxc6  bxc6  14.Qa6+  Kd7  15.Na5  Qe6  16.c4  Be7  17.Rfd1  Black played a few more moves but could have safely resigned in Fischer-Shipman, New York 1971.   Leela suggests that  6...Bf5  is playable, but I am reluctant to recommend the position after  7.O-O  Qd6  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.Ba6  which looks worse to me, or at the very least hard to play for Black. }
7. Nxc6 bxc6
{ 7...Nxc6  8.Qxe4   8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.Qxe4  Bd6  saw White going for the repetition with  10.Qxc6+  Bd7  11.Qe4+  Be6  12.Qc6+  Bd7  13.Qe4+  in Phillips-Lanz Calavia, ICCF 2017.  8...Qd7  seems to give questionable compensation.   8...Bd6  9.d4  O-O  10.Bd3  g6  11.O-O  looks bad too.  Stockfish's preference for  9.d4  may not even be that clear, but the simple  9.Bc4  O-O-O  10.Bxe6  fxe6  11.O-O  is enough for me to dismiss the line. Black is a pawn down and  11...e5  12.b4!  with Na3-c4 coming, certainly doesn't look pleasant. }
8. Ba6 Qd7
{ Once again, we are following Sokolov's analysis. This pawn sacrifice is fully justified.   Instead,  8...Qd5  9.O-O  Ng6  10.Re1!  makes it hard for Black to hold on to the e-pawn. For instance  10...f5  11.d3!  and Black is collapsing.   10...Bd6  is a better try, but I still think  11.Qxe4  Qh5  12.g3  O-O  13.Be2!  is better for White.  @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/p1p2ppp/B1p1b1n1/3q4/4p3/2P5/PP1PQPPP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10.d3  exd3  11.Bxd3  is how that game of Gupta continued, with a slightly better position for White. In the game Black quickly lost after  11...O-O-O?  12.Rd1  Kb8  13.Bc2  winning material. So-Gupta, Dubai 2008. }
9. O-O Ng6
{ New and, from what I can see, strong.   9...Nd5  10.Qxe4  Bd6  11.d4  O-O  12.Qc2  c5  13.dxc5  Bxc5  14.Nd2  h6  was twice drawn by correspondence player Velker, but I think the text move is more sound. }
10. Qxe4 Be7
{ Black plans to castle and bring the bishop to d5, starting a slow attack. }
11. Na3 { The computer suggestion but not the move that comes to mind first. }
11... O-O { We just continue development. } 12. Nc2
{ White would like to bring the knight over to e3 and consolidate. It is time to get active! }
12... Bd5 13. Qa4 Bxg2
{ 13...Bd6  14.Ne3  Bf3!!  is a wonderful idea, but on move 14 White can improve with  14.f3  . }
14. Kxg2 Nh4+ 15. Kg3 { We get to take the white king out for a walk! } 15...
Qf5
{ Black has a multitude of options. Both  15...Bd6+  16.f4  g5  and even the slow  15...Rae8  16.Qg4  f5  17.Qc4+  Kh8  come into consideration. }
16. f4 { The only move, and the next few moves are forced as well. } 16... Qg6+
17. Kf2 Bc5+ 18. Ne3 { This seems to hold for White. } 18... Qg2+ 19. Ke1 Bxe3
20. dxe3 Rad8 21. Rf2 Nf3+ 22. Ke2 Ng1+ 23. Ke1 Nf3+
{ A repetition neither side can  (properly)  avoid. } *

