{ This contains a nice trick.   14...Bxg2  15.Kxg2  Nf4+  16.Kh1  Qh3  still doesn't quite work, this time because of  17.Bxh7+  Kh8  18.Qe4!  Bd6  19.Bf5  Qh5  20.Qf3  Qxf5  21.Nc4!  which exchanges a few pieces and secures an advantage for White. And @@StartFEN@@4rr1k/p1p1bppB/2p5/8/3PQn2/2P4q/PP1N1P1P/R1B2R1K b - - 2 18@@EndFEN@@  18...f5  19.Qf3  Qxh7  20.Nc4  is good for White too. }
15. dxc5 Bxg2 { With the d-file opened, this sacrifice gains in power. } 16.
Bxg6
{ A good intermediate move, not allowing the check on f4 after recapturing on g2.   16.Kxg2  Allows Black to illustrate why it was important to open the d-file.  16...Nf4+  17.Kh1  Nxd3  Things have gone terribly out of control for White. }
16... fxg6 17. Kxg2 Bxc5
{ White is a piece up but the pressure is enormous. With ideas like ...Re8-e2, ...Rf8-f5 and ...Qd7-g4, it will be hard for White to survive the next 5 moves. }
