{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. O-O
{ By far the most popular move in the position, and a logical one obviously. }
4... g6
{ With the knight on e7, the plan to fianchetto the bishop on g7 is the most sensible approach. }
5. d4 { Contrary to 4.Nc3, 5.d4 here is much less dangerous. } 5... exd4 6. c3
{ A pawn sacrifice that we need to take notice of. Accepting it is more or less obliged, as we can't allow White to set up a big centre with cxd4 next move. }
6... dxc3 7. Nxc3 Bg7
{ It is important that we get developed as quickly as we can, before White gets Bc1-g5 and Nc3-d5 in. }
8. Nd5 a6 9. Ba4 h6
{ I like this move a lot, stopping Bc1-g5 indefinitely.   9...O-O  10.Bg5  forces us to go  10...f6  which is something I would prefer to avoid, if possible. }
10. Bf4 d6 11. Nxe7
{ White has to play concrete.   A slow move like  11.Qd2  allows  11...g5!  12.Be3  O-O  when Black is doing well. }
11... Qxe7 12. e5 { Forcing mass simplifications. } 12... dxe5 13. Bxc6+ bxc6
14. Bxe5 O-O
{ Technically speaking we are still a pawn up, but the doubled c-pawns make the position approximately equal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: Normal Development - 4.0-0"]
[Black "Cozio Defence 4.0-0 g6 5.d4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. O-O
{ By far the most popular move in the position, and a logical one obviously. }
4... g6
{ With the knight on e7, the plan to fianchetto the bishop on g7 is the most sensible approach. }
5. d4 { Contrary to 4.Nc3, 5.d4 here is much less dangerous. } 5... exd4 6. c3
{ A pawn sacrifice that we need to take notice of. Accepting it is more or less obliged, as we can't allow White to set up a big centre with cxd4 next move. }
6... dxc3 7. Bxc6
{ This move is White's most tricky response and contains a few traps. } 7...
Nxc6
{ It is easy to fall for  7...bxc6  8.Qd4!  and Black is in deep trouble. See for instance  8...cxb2  9.Bxb2  Rg8  10.Nbd2  Rb8  11.e5!  planning Nd2-e4, with great pressure. The black king is stuck on  e8  .   More serious is the alternative  7...Bg7!?  which I think is fully playable. Black's idea is to play  bxc6  if White recaptures on  c3  and that's why  8.Bxd7+  is critical. Now  8...Qxd7  9.Qe2!?  keeps the queens on the board and leads to interesting play. I think Black is ok though, after  9...c2!?  10.Nc3  Qc6  11.Qxc2  Bg4  . }
8. Nxc3 Bg7 9. Bg5
{ This is another point behind White's 7th move. Black is forced to weaken the pawn structure with ...f7-f6. }
9... f6 10. Bf4 O-O 11. Qb3+ Rf7 { 11...Kh8  is possible as well. } 12. Nd5 d6
{ Time to take stock. We are a pawn up but it's obvious White has some pressure in return. With our last move, we are preparing ...Nc6-e5. }
13. Rac1 Na5
{ Kicking the queen from b3, so that the rook is no longer pinned.   After the planned  13...Ne5  , White makes use of that pin by playing  14.Nxc7  . }
14. Qa3 Nc6 { Once again threatening ...Nc6-e5. } 15. Qb3
{ And White prevents the knight jump once more. } 15... Na5
{ With a natural repetition of moves.   Black could try playing for more with  15...g5  16.Be3  h6  but it's not easy to find a clear way to improve the position after, say,  17.Rfe1  . }
*

