{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. O-O
{ By far the most popular move in the position, and a logical one obviously. }
4... g6
{ With the knight on e7, the plan to fianchetto the bishop on g7 is the most sensible approach. }
5. d4 { Contrary to 4.Nc3, 5.d4 here is much less dangerous. } 5... exd4 6.
Nxd4 Bg7
{ The differences between 4.Nc3 and 4.O-O are big. Let's investigate! } 7. Be3
O-O 8. Nc3 d5 { The equalizer. } 9. exd5 Nb4
{ And not  9...Nxd5  as after  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Nxd5!  wins an exchange after both  11...cxd5  12.Bc5!  and  11...Qxd5  12.Qxd5  cxd5  13.Bc5  Rd8  14.Bc6  Rb8  15.Be7  . }
10. Bg5 h6
{ Not the weakening  10...f6  after which  11.Bh4  Nbxd5  12.Nxd5  Nxd5  13.Re1  was clearly better for White in Wojtaszek-Ashiev, Internet Blitz 2020. }
11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. a3
{ This would be great for White it not for the following forcing solution. }
12... Bxd4 13. axb4 Bg7 14. Ra4 { The only way to defend the b-pawn. } 14... a6
15. Re1 Qd6 16. Bf1 Bd7 { Black wins back the pawn. } 17. b5 axb5 18. Rxa8 Rxa8
19. Bxb5 { This runs into an intermediate move. } 19... Bxc3
{ After  20.bxc3  Bxb5  , Black remains a piece up. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: Normal Development - 4.0-0"]
[Black "Cozio 4.0-0 g6 5.c3 - Old Main Line [informational]"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. O-O
{ By far the most popular move in the position, and a logical one obviously. }
4... g6
{ With the knight on e7, the plan to fianchetto the bishop on g7 is the most sensible approach. }
5. c3
{ Preparing to build a big centre with d2-d4 next. This move is the overwhelming favourite in practical play, with well over a 1000 games to prove it. }
5... Bg7 { This is the old main line. } 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 d5
{ Black is in big strategic trouble after a simple move. } 8. Bxc6+
{ Black faces a choice of how to recapture. } 8... Nxc6
{ 8...bxc6  9.e5  O-O  10.h3  isn't great, since Black's dark squares are severely weakened. The break  10...f6  11.exf6  Bxf6  doesn't help much following the accurate sequence  12.Bh6  Re8  13.Re1  Nf5  14.Rxe8+  Qxe8  15.Bf4!  c5  16.Nc3!  and engines already jump way up. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/p1p1npbp/2p3p1/3pP3/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bg4  10.Nbd2  and h2-h3 next, also doesn't promise Black full play. }
9. exd5 Ne7
{ An important question to answer. If Black gets to take back on d5 and simply castle kingside, White will have nothing.   9...Qxd5  10.Nc3!  is even worse. }
10. Nc3 O-O
{ 10...Nxd5  11.Bg5!  is very strong, since  11...f6  runs into  12.Re1+  Kf7  13.Re5!!  with the idea that  13...Nxc3  14.Qb3+  Kf8  15.bxc3  fxg5  16.Nxg5  Qf6  17.Rae1  Bd7  18.Re7  is winning for White. }
11. Qb3 { Now Black will have a hard time winning back the pawn. } 11... b6 12.
Bg5 Bb7 13. Rae1 Re8 14. Re3 { Keeping the pressure. } 14... Qd7 15. Ne5 Qd6
16. Nxf7 Kxf7 17. Bf4 Qxf4 18. d6+ Kf8 19. dxe7+ Rxe7 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. Qxd5
{ Threatening both Re3-f3 and Qd5xa8. } 21... c6 22. Qxc6 Qb8 23. Rxe7 Kxe7 24.
Qf3 Bf6 25. g4 Qd8 26. Re1+ Kd6 27. d5 Kc7 28. d6+ Kb8 29. d7
{ White wins. These are some very tough lines, and it serves as a reminder that theory and practice are often two completely different worlds. I am pretty sure I would never find this sequence over the board. }
*

