5... a6 { An improvement over theold main line. } 6. Ba4 Bg7 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4
b5
{ The big difference with 5...Bg7 is that Black first chases the bishop, before playing ...d7-d5. That turns out to be significant.   Here too,  8...d5  9.exd5  Nxd5  is worse. White has serious pressure after  10.Bg5!  Qd6  11.Nbd2  O-O  12.Nc4  which is why we include ...b7-b5. }
9. Bb3
{ By far the most played move in the position, though considered less critical. I think the popularity is explained by the fact that the text move looks more normal than9.Bc2 and is easily played 'by hand'. }
9... O-O 10. Nc3 Na5
{ Starting with this move or  10...d6  , likely doesn't matter much, but the text move is a bit more forceful. }
11. Bc2 d6 12. h3
{ White's last move makes sure ...Bc8-g4 isn't a threat anymore. } 12... c5
{ An essential part of Black's strategy, attacking the White centre. } 13. d5
{ A drastic decision, closing the centre. Hikaru Nakamura has used this move twice and with success, though it should be said both games involved a quick play tempo. }
13... Nc4
{ 13...Bd7!?  is interesting too. It makes a future manoeuvre ...Ne7-c8-b6 possible and prepares queenside play with ...b5-b4. }
14. Bd3 Ne5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Bh6
{ Here Leela takes over and she does so in style! } 16... b4
{ Ignoring White's previous move. } 17. Na4 Rb8 18. a3 a5 19. axb4 axb4 20.
Bxf8 { What else? A rook is still a rook! } 20... Qxf8 21. f4 Bd4+ 22. Kh1 Bd7
{ A great position! The knight on a4 is completely out of play and the bishop on d4 is an absolute monster. Despite the engines still assessing this as approximately equal, I'd take Black here without a doubt.   A sample line is  23.b3  g5!?  24.fxg5  Bxa1  25.Qxa1  Bxa4  26.Qxa4  Ng6  and ...Ne5 comes next. }
*

