3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. O-O
{ By far the most popular move in the position, and a logical one obviously. }
4... g6
{ With the knight on e7, the plan to fianchetto the bishop on g7 is the most sensible approach. }
5. c3
{ Preparing to build a big centre with d2-d4 next. This move is the overwhelming favourite in practical play, with well over a 1000 games to prove it. }
5... a6 { An improvement over theold main line. } 6. Ba4 Bg7 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4
b5
{ The big difference with 5...Bg7 is that Black first chases the bishop, before playing ...d7-d5. That turns out to be significant.   Here too,  8...d5  9.exd5  Nxd5  is worse. White has serious pressure after  10.Bg5!  Qd6  11.Nbd2  O-O  12.Nc4  which is why we include ...b7-b5. }
9. Bc2
{ Considered smart, as retreating to b3 makes the bishop vulnerable to ...Nc6-a5. }
9... d5 10. exd5 Nb4
{ A key element in Black's plan. Black attacks the bishop on c2 and prepares the recapture on d5. Taking on d5 immediately with either queen or knight is not recommended.   10...Qxd5  11.Nc3  Qd7  12.Re1  O-O  13.d5  Nb4  14.Bb3  Bb7  15.Bg5  gave White a big advantage in Costa Trillo-Avellan, Correspondence Chess 2015, as  15...Nexd5  16.a3!  loses material.   10...Nxd5  11.Bg5!  also doesn't offer much respite, as practice has shown. Aronian once played  11...Nde7  here, but  12.Be4!  casts doubt on that setup since the threat of taking either knight is hard to meet. If the ugly move  12...f6  is indeed forced, that is a bad sign! }
11. Bb3 Nbxd5 12. Nc3 O-O
{ With the king out of the centre, Black is close to solving all opening problems. }
13. Re1 { Played by Fabiano Caruana in a blitz game against Anish Giri. } 13...
Nf6
{ A typical move in this line. It prevents Nc3-e4 and prepares ...Bc8-b7.   The aforementioned game continued  13...h6  when  14.Nxd5  Nxd5  15.Ne5  is quite unpleasant. Black can't develop the bishop to  e6  as that allows the knight to take on  g6  , but  15...Bb7  16.Qf3  Qd6  17.Bd2  is unpleasant as well. Black is tied up. }
14. Ne5 Bb7 { ...Ne7-f5 is coming next and Black is in great shape. } *

