{ Considered smart, as retreating to b3 makes the bishop vulnerable to ...Nc6-a5. }
9... d5 10. exd5 Nb4
{ A key element in Black's plan. Black attacks the bishop on c2 and prepares the recapture on d5. Taking on d5 immediately with either queen or knight is not recommended.   10...Qxd5  11.Nc3  Qd7  12.Re1  O-O  13.d5  Nb4  14.Bb3  Bb7  15.Bg5  gave White a big advantage in Costa Trillo-Avellan, Correspondence Chess 2015, as  15...Nexd5  16.a3!  loses material.   10...Nxd5  11.Bg5!  also doesn't offer much respite, as practice has shown. Aronian once played  11...Nde7  here, but  12.Be4!  casts doubt on that setup since the threat of taking either knight is hard to meet. If the ugly move  12...f6  is indeed forced, that is a bad sign! }
11. Bb3 Nbxd5 12. Bg5 h6
{ I first discovered this move in 2017 but by now it has already been introduced in practice. Engines need a while to figure out what is going on here.   The old move is  12...Qd6  but it has been established that  13.Nbd2  O-O  14.Rc1  Bf5  15.Re1  as in Adams-J.Van Foreest, Douglas 2014, is somewhat unpleasant for Black. }
13. Bh4 g5 14. Bg3 O-O
{ The most natural move.   Correspondence practice has seen  14...Bg4!?  15.Nc3  Nf4  16.Bxf4  gxf4  which seems to be fine as well. I see no reason for such 'desperation' though. We can also equalize by normal means. }
15. Nc3 Be6
{ Black is fully mobilized and it is clear that equality is not far off. } 16.
Re1 Nxc3 { 16...Ng6!?  is possible too. } 17. bxc3 Bxb3 18. axb3 Ng6
{ Black is OK!   A sample line is  19.b4  c6  20.Qd2  Bf6  Prepares for the h2-h4 advance.  21.h4  gxh4  22.Bf4  Qd5!  23.Bxh6  Rfe8  and Black is very active. White should take care not to take the pawn with  24.Rxe8+  Rxe8  25.Rxa6  as  25...h3!  is very unpleasant. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: Chasing the Knight - 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.h4 Nd4 6.h5"]
[Black "Cozio Defence 4.Nc3 g6 - 6.Nd5 [informational]"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. Nc3
{ This natural developing move has taken centre stage over the past few years. It is aimed against the move ...g7-g6. I start this chapter with two Informationals, explaining my preference for  4...Ng6  , instead of the more popular  4...g6  . }
4... g6 5. d4 exd4 6. Nd5
{ Considered by most to be the critical direction, but I think  6.Nxd4  is much stronger. }
6... Bg7 { Protecting against mate in 1, while developing the bishop. } 7. Bg5
{ Threatening to win material with Bb5xc6, forcing Black's next move. } 7... h6
8. Bf6 Bxf6 9. Nxf6+ Kf8 { The critical position. } 10. Qd2
{ 10.Nxd4  Kg7  11.Qd2!  was an amazing discovery by Jacob Murey, introduced against Alexei Dreev in Moscow 1989. The idea is that  11...Kxf6  12.Qc3!  leads to deadly threats on the long diagonal.   Later on it was found that  10.Nxd4  can be met with  10...Nf5!  which is why the modern treatment is to reverse the move order. By starting with 10.Qd2! White avoids the crafty resource of ...Ne7-f5.   10.O-O!?  is interesting too, though black should be holding the endgame that arises after  10...a6  11.Bc4  Kg7  12.Nxd4  Ne5   not  12...Kxf6  13.Qf3+!  and White wins the house.  13.Nf3  N7c6  14.Nxe5  Qxf6  15.Ng4  Qd4!  despite White still having an edge. }
10... d5
{ 10...Kg7  11.Nxd4!  transposes to the Murey-game.   10...Ng8  is very passive. Simply  11.Nxg8  Kxg8  12.O-O-O  and Nf3xd4 next, is a risk-free and serious advantage.   10...a6  11.Bc4  Nf5  is an attempt to nevertheless get the ...Ne7-f5 idea to work, but  12.Nd5  Nd6  13.Qd3  is pretty bad for Black. Black's position lacks harmony. }
11. Bxc6 Nxc6 12. Nxd5 Bf5
{ Very strong. Black needs to undermine the position of the knight on d5 and this move serves that purpose perfectly.   12...Be6  13.c4!  is great for White, as  13...dxc3  14.Qxc3  creates big threats on the long diagonal. }
13. Qf4
{ 13.Nxd4  fails tactically,  13...Bxe4  14.Nxc6  . The pitfall to avoid is  14...bxc6  15.Qc3!  which sees White winning on the spot.  @@StartFEN@@r2q1k1r/ppp2p2/2N3pp/3N4/4b3/8/PPPQ1PPP/R3K2R b KQ - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Qxd5!  15.Qc3  With a knight on c6, instead of d5, the threats on the long diagonal are much less scary.  15...Rh7  16.Qb4+  Qd6!  White is in big trouble, as the endgame after  17.Qxd6+  cxd6  is very bad. White is dropping a pawn. And if  17.Qxe4?  Re8  loses the queen.     13.Nxc7!?  tried by Giri back in 2015, and a try to fight for the advantage by having the better pawn structure. Black is active enough to comfortably hold the balance though.  13...Qxc7  14.exf5  Re8+  It is important for Black to have this check in order to stop the White king from being able to castle.  15.Kf1  gxf5   It's not out of the question to play  15...g5  in order to keep the structure intact and attempt to win the f5-pawn back at a later stage.  16.g3  Re4  17.Kg2  Kg7  18.Rhe1  Qd7  19.Nh4  Rhe8  and now  20.f3  Rxe1  21.Rxe1  Rxe1  22.Qxe1  Qd5  the position is roughly equal. Yes, Black's pawn structure is sub-optimal, but that's compensated by White's knight which is out of play on h4. Black will grab space on the queenside next, with ...a7-a5 and ...b7-b5. }
13... Bxe4 14. Qxe4 Qd6
{ The way in correspondence chess has been  14...Kg7  but I dislike the endgame after  15.O-O   15.O-O-O  Re8  16.Qxe8  Qxe8  17.Nxc7  Qd8  18.Nxa8  b5!  19.Rhe1  Qxa8  20.Rd3   20.Nxd4  Nxd4  21.Rxd4  Qxg2  illustrates why Black's 18th move received an exclaim.  20...Qd8  21.a3  Qa5  22.g3  b4  23.Red1  Qa6  24.h4  bxa3  25.Rxa3  Qc4  26.Ne1  a5  27.Nd3  a4  28.Re1  Na5  29.Re5  was agreed drawn in Suárez Rodríguez-Ivanov, Correspondence Chess 2019. It indeed looks like Black has managed to organize enough counterplay.  15...Re8  16.Qxe8  Qxe8  17.Nxc7  Qd8  18.Nxa8  Qxa8  19.Rfd1  which is very one-sided. Black may hold the draw, but also may not. In any case, not something I feel is fun to play in a practical game. }
15. Nxc7 Qxc7 16. O-O-O Re8 17. Qh4 Re2
{ An important new move.   Previously it was thought that  17...g5  18.Qg3  Qxg3  19.hxg3  was forced. This endgame is very ugly for Black and in for instance the Strömberg-Mozelius, Correspondence Chess 2015, White indeed won. @@StartFEN@@4rk1r/ppq2p2/2n4p/6p1/3p3Q/5N2/PPP2PPP/2KR3R w - - 0 18@@EndFEN@@ Another important point to make is that  18.Nxg5  Nb4!  19.Rd2  Nxa2+  20.Kb1  Nc3+!  is the reason taking on  g5  doesn't promise White anything. Following  21.bxc3  Qb6+  22.Kc1  dxc3  23.Ne6+!  Rxe6  24.Rd8+  Kg7  25.Qg3+!  the pawn on  c3  will fall and White manages to hold on - but not from a position of strength. }
18. Qf6 { This looks very menacing, but in reality isn't too worrying. } 18...
Kg8
{ Intending ...Kg8-h7 when the king is safe and the h8-rook ready to join the action. }
19. Rhe1 Rxe1 20. Rxe1 Kh7
{ Just in time! White has no way of strengthening the position further and should grab the pawn on d4. }
21. Nxd4 Nxd4 22. Qxd4 Rc8
{ A necessary intermediate move.   Starting with  22...Qxh2  leads to trouble after  23.g3  when both of Black's heavy pieces are out of play. Concretely, after  23...a6  24.Qf6!  Rf8  25.Qf3!  White has the twin threat of taking on b7 and playing Re1-h1. After the text move, Black holds in all the lines. }
23. c3 Qxh2 24. Qf6 Rf8
{ 24...Kg8  25.Re7  Rf8  26.Qf3!  wins a pawn on the queenside. } 25. g3 Qh3
{ 25...Kg8  once again runs into  26.Qf3! } 26. Re7 Qh1+ 27. Kc2 Kg8 28. a4
{ It makes sense to push the queenside, as the eventual plan must be to take Black's pawns on the queenside and queen one of the passed pawns.   The engine suggestion is  28.Qd4  a6  29.Re4  but it's not clear what this achieves after, say,  29...Qh3!?  intending to bring the queen back in the game to f5 or c8. }
28... a6 29. Qb6 Qa1
{ From a1 the queen does a surprisingly good job finding counterplay. Black has other options but I prefer this one. }
30. Re4 h5
{ So that in the future Black can easily create a passed pawn with ...g6-g5 and ...h5-h4. Black is OK. }
31. Qxb7 Rd8 { A sudden mating threat appears on d1. } 32. Rd4 Rxd4 33. cxd4
Qxa4+ 34. Kc3 Qa5+
{ The position is equal as Black will keep checking and has a potential passed pawn on the kingside as well. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: Chasing the Knight - 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.h4 Nd4 6.h5"]
[Black "Cozio Defence 4.Nc3 g6 - 6.Nxd4 [informational]"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. Nc3
{ This natural developing move has taken centre stage over the past few years. It is aimed against the move ...g7-g6. I start this chapter with two Informationals, explaining my preference for  4...Ng6  , instead of the more popular  4...g6  . }
4... g6 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4
{ In the previous Informational we have seen that the traditional main line, with  6.Nd5  , probably holds for Black. We now come to the big issue of this variation and the reason I don't recommend 4...g6. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3 { 7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.Ba4  O-O  9.Be3  transposes. } 7... O-O 8.
Nxc6
{ An extremely rare move in this position, but the reason that I feel this line is not recommendable. }
8... bxc6
{ 8...dxc6  9.Bd3  is undesirable for Black, from a structural viewpoint.   8...Nxc6  9.Qd2  isn't advisable either. White simply wants to push h2-h4-h5 etc. }
9. Ba4
{ Modern engines immediately point at this direction, but at first sight it doesn't look obvious that this position is dangerous for Black. }
9... d5
{ After  9...d6  10.Bd4  both this and  10.Qd2  , I feel offer White the better game.   Neither does  9...Ba6  10.Bd4!  , exchanging the strong bishop, offer Black an equal game. }
10. Bc5
{ The important point. Suddenly Black's position looks bad as the bishops reign supreme. }
10... dxe4 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. Bxe7
{ Obviously loses a piece. I spent considerable time trying to make something work after 8.Nxc6 but did not succeed. Perhaps an interesting challenge for the reader of these lines! Now that we know what we don't want to play, let's look at some lines that we do want to play! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: Chasing the Knight - 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.h4 Nd4 6.h5"]
[Black "Cozio Defence 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.h4 - 5th moves [informational]"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. Nc3
{ This natural developing move has taken centre stage over the past few years. It is aimed against the move ...g7-g6. I started this chapter with two Informationals, explaining my preference for  4...Ng6  , instead of the more popular  4...g6  . In this third Informational, we start exploring the  4...Ng6  variations and the lines we should avoid. }
4... Ng6
{ Leads to a completely different type of game. Suddenly we are facing the Spanish Variation of the Four Knights Game where Black has spent two moves placing the knight on g6, instead of the usual square f6. There are ups and downs to this setup.   From g6 the knight does an excellent job protecting the e5-pawn and it can potentially jump to the active square f4. The downside is obviously that spending two moves on getting the knight to g6 is rather time consuming. The question is if White can punish this loss of time. One thing is for sure, Black's 4th move leads to original play and unexplored territory.   The very first -recorded- game with the Cozio Defence continued  4...a6  which is supposed to be inaccurate.  If Black wants to include ...a7-a6, it should be done on move 3.  Now  5.Bc4!?  is a strong alternative to going to a4.  5...Na5  6.Nxe5   6.Be2!?  may even be stronger, when Black has nothing better than  6...Nac6  when  7.d4  secures a serious advantage: Black has lost too much time.  6...Nxc4  7.Nxc4  d5  @@StartBracket@@Von Heydebrand und der Lasa-Spaeter, Berlin 1836@@EndBracket@@, and here  8.exd5  Nxd5  9.O-O  is a reasonably healthy extra pawn for White.  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pppnppp/p1n5/4p3/2B1P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...d6  with the idea  6.Ng5  d5  7.exd5  Na5  may be worth investigating. It's a weird version of the Two Knights Defence. }
5. h4
{ Bologan's move and a very logical and direct attempt to refute Black's setup. It questions the manoeuvre ...Ne7-g6 by preparing h4-h5. }
5... Be7
{ A logical reply. Black continues development while attacking the h-pawn.   5...Nf4  is no solution, as  6.d3!  Nxg2+  7.Kf1  Nf4  8.Bxf4  exf4  9.d4  gives White a big advantage in the centre.   After  5...h5  the big question is which side profits from including the moves 5.h4 h5. I feel, in this case, it is probably White. Critical is the position that arises after  6.d4  Nxd4  7.Nxd4  exd4  8.Qxd4  c6  9.Be2  Qb6   9...Nxh4  10.f4  Nxg2+  11.Kf1  Nh4  12.f5!  is very dangerous for Black.  10.Qd3  Bc5  11.O-O  Qc7  when Black wants to ...Ng6-f4 next. Even though it looks like a weakening move, I was unable to equalize the move  12.g3  with the very bold plan of playing Kg1-g2 next and possibly Qd3-d1, picking up the h5-pawn. Note that the immediate Qd3-d1 loses to Qc7xg3+!   Last but not least, the stem game Bologan-Arkhipov, Moscow 1995 continued  5...Bc5  6.h5  Nf8  7.Nxe5  Nxe5  8.d4  Bd6  9.dxe5  Bxe5  10.f4  Bxc3+  11.bxc3  when White had a large advantage based on space and the bishop pair. }
6. Nd5 { Simply intending to take the bishop on e7. } 6... Bxh4
{ Taking with the knight feels dangerous, because of  6...Nxh4  7.Nxh4  Bxh4  8.Qh5!  Be7  9.f4!  with the idea that  9...exf4  10.c3!  prepares d2-d4 and is highly dangerous for Black. }
7. d4 { This pawn push casts doubt on Black's 5th move. } 7... Nxd4 8. Nxd4
{ 8.Nxh4  Nxh4  transposes to 7.Nxh4. } 8... exd4 9. Qxd4
{ An extremely dangerous position for Black. } 9... O-O
{ 9...c6  10.Rxh4  Qxh4  11.Nc7+  Kd8  12.Nxa8  cxb5  13.Be3  is bad. The key line is  13...Qh1+  14.Kd2  Qxa1  15.Bg5+!  f6  16.Bxf6+  gxf6  17.Qxf6+  and Black is doomed as  17...Ke8  18.Nc7!  is mate.  And  17...Ne7  18.Qxh8+  also won't make the game last @@StartBracket@@much@@EndBracket@@ longer.  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1p1ppp/2p3n1/1B1N4/3QP2R/8/PPP2PP1/R1B1K3 b Qkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...cxd5  11.Rg4!  Qa5+  12.Bd2  Qxb5  13.a4!  turns out to be very dangerous for Black as well. Given that I am not recommending any of this I will just give an illustrative line, rather than going into too much detail. After  13...Qb6  14.Qxg7  Rf8  15.O-O-O  d4  16.Bh6  -with the intention to take on g6 next move-  16...Qc5  17.Rg5  Qe7  18.Qxd4  Rg8  19.f4  White has a huge initiative. }
10. g3 Be7
{ 10...Bf6  11.Nxf6+  Qxf6  12.Qxf6  gxf6  13.f3  is a sad endgame for Black. }
11. Bd2 Re8 12. O-O-O Bf8 13. Rh5 c6 14. Rdh1 cxd5
{ Or  14...h6  15.Bxh6!  crashing through. } 15. Rxh7 Qf6 16. e5 Rxe5 17. Qd3
{ Threatening mate in two, starting with Rh8+. } 17... Qf5 18. f4 Qxd3 19. Bxd3
{ Once again, threatening Rh8+ and mate next move. On top of that, f4-f5 is a big threat. Black is lost. }
