[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: Chasing the Knight - 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.h4 Nd4 6.h5"]
[Black "Cozio Defence 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.h4 Nd4 - 6.Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. Nc3
{ This natural developing move has taken centre stage over the past few years. It is aimed against the move ...g7-g6. }
4... Ng6
{ Leads to a completely different type of game. Suddenly we are facing the Spanish Variation of the Four Knights Game where Black has spent two moves placing the knight on g6, instead of the usual square f6. There are ups and downs to this setup but one thing is for sure, it leads to original games and unexplored territory.   For  4...a6  and  4...g6  , see theInformationals at the beginning of the chapter. }
5. h4
{ Bologan's move and a very logical and direct attempt to refute Black's setup. It questions the manoeuvre ...Ne7-g6 by preparing h4-h5. }
5... Nd4
{ Rare, but the only move that offers Black a good game. White's bishop is hanging on b5 and Black quite literally stops the d2-d4 push from happening. }
6. Nxd4 exd4 7. Ne2 c6
{ Gives Black a fine game, note that the pawn on  h4  merely constitutes a weakness here. A sample line is  8.Bc4  Nxh4  9.Kf1  Qg5!  10.Ng3  Be7  11.d3  Qg6  , when it's not easy to see where White's compensation should be coming from.   An illustration how rich the position is shows if Black choses, after  8.Bc4  , not to take on  h4  , but rather sacrifice a few pawns for activity.  8...d5!?  9.exd5  b5  10.Bb3  d3!?  is a very interesting way of playing. Following  11.cxd3  Bd6  Black will continue quick development and will have excellent compensation for the pawns.   We can safely conclude that taking on d4 on move six is not a logical follow-up of 5.h4 and gives Black too many options. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: Chasing the Knight - 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.h4 Nd4 6.h5"]
[Black "Cozio Defence 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.h4 Nd4 - 6.h5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. Nc3
{ This natural developing move has taken centre stage over the past few years. It is aimed against the move ...g7-g6. }
4... Ng6
{ Leads to a completely different type of game. Suddenly we are facing the Spanish Variation of the Four Knights Game where Black has spent two moves placing the knight on g6, instead of the usual square f6. There are ups and downs to this setup but one thing is for sure, it leads to original games and unexplored territory.   For  4...a6  and  4...g6  , see theInformationals at the beginning of the chapter. }
5. h4
{ Bologan's move and a very logical and direct attempt to refute Black's setup. It questions the manoeuvre ...Ne7-g6 by preparing h4-h5. }
5... Nd4
{ Rare, but the only move that offers Black a good game. White's bishop is hanging on b5 and Black quite literally stops the d2-d4 push from happening. }
6. h5
{ Together with  6.Bc4  , the most consistent move.  White tries to prove that the manoeuvre ...Ne7-g6 is flawed - it is not! }
6... Nf4 7. g3
{ Continuing to harrass the knight, e6 is an excellent square though. } 7...
Nfe6
{ A good pawn sacrifice.   7...Nxf3+  8.Qxf3  Ne6  9.h6!?  is also not that bad for Black, but not entirely to my liking. White keeps some nagging pressure. }
8. Nxe5
{ The most principled response.   8.Bc4  Nxf3+  9.Qxf3  h6  is fine for Black as the following line  10.Bxe6  dxe6  11.d3  Qd7!?  illustrates. With ...b7-b6, ...Bc8-b7, ...O-O-O, ...f7-f6 coming, Black has many easy moves that improve the position. }
8... Nxb5 9. Nxb5 d5 10. d4
{ 10.Qf3  f6!  followed by ...Ne6-g5 wins back the pawn and secures a good game.   Even worse is  10.d3  c6  11.Nc3  when  11...d4!  followed by ...Qd8-a5+ wins material. }
10... c6 11. Nc3 dxe4 12. d5 { 12.Be3  Bb4  shouldn't worry Black. } 12... cxd5
13. Nxd5 f6 14. h6
{ An attempt to set the board on fire!   I like  14.Nc4  Kf7!?  for Black, as we have a clear plan of going ...b7-b6, ...Bc8-b7, ...Bf8-c5 and get our pieces into the game. Long-term, because of the bishop pair, Black's prospects should be good. }
14... fxe5
{ Less adventurous is  14...g6!?  15.Ng4  Be7  , which is dynamically even. }
15. Qh5+ g6 16. Qxe5 Qd6 { An excellent response! } 17. Qxh8
{ Very dangerous for White. In the upcoming complications, Black gets to hit first. }
17... Qxd5 18. Qxh7 Bb4+ 19. Kf1
{ White's best bet.   Worse is  19.c3  Nf8  20.Qg7  e3!  which gives Black a better version of the text move. After  21.Rh4  exf2+  22.Kxf2  Bc5+  Black is winning, as  23.Be3  Qd2+!  is there. }
19... Nf8 20. Qg7 e3
{ The h-pawn is a dangerous runner, but White will get no time to promote it. For now, the h1-rook is threatened. }
21. Rh4 Qd1+ 22. Kg2 exf2 { Black is dictating play. } 23. Re4+ Be6 24. Rxe6+
Nxe6 25. Qxg6+ Kd7 26. Qf7+ Be7
{ After a long and forced variation, it seems Black is doing well. The h-pawn is no longer as dangerous as it was some 10 moves ago, and we have an extra knight! Perhaps most importantly, the king on d7 is in a much safer space than its counterpart on g2. }
*

