14... fxe5
{ Less adventurous is  14...g6!?  15.Ng4  Be7  , which is dynamically even. }
15. Qh5+ g6 16. Qxe5 Qd6 { An excellent response! } 17. Qxe4 Be7 18. O-O O-O
19. Rd1
{ 19.Bf4  is met with the exchange sacrifice  19...Rxf4!  20.gxf4  Bf8  when  21.Rad1  Nc7!  secures the position. Once  h6  falls and the bishop gets to  f5  , things could get dangerous for White. }
19... Qd8
{ The final accurate move. Black is ready to give up the queen for the greater good! }
20. Nf6+ Bxf6 21. Rxd8 Nxd8
{ Time to take stock. Black has a rook, bishop and knight for a queen and two pawns − not a bad trade. More importantly, with the bishop coming to f5 on the next move, Black's position looks harmonious and the pieces work well together, which is important for the side with the higher quantity of pieces. The engines think the position is approximately even and that sounds right. }
*

