{ 8...Qg5  9.Nd5  Nxd5  10.exd5  Be7  is one of those positions that is close to equal, but just not fully. The pawn on h5 and slight lead in development make that White can still press a bit starting with  11.d3  .   8...g5?  9.hxg6  Nxg6  10.Nd5!  is the big difference with 8.Qg4. }
9. d3
{ Trying to induce  9...Ne6  , after which  10.Ne2  gives White a pleasant structural edge. }
9... dxc3 10. Bxf4 cxb2 11. Rb1 Bxf4 12. Qxf4
{ A big transformation has taken place and White is trying to claim a small advantage based on a small lead in development, the annoying pawn on h5 and the extra central pawn. It turns out not to be a big deal. }
12... c6 13. Bc4 Qe7
{ The endgame after  13...Qf6  14.Qxf6  gxf6  is certainly possible as well. Black should be able to draw the position after  15.f3  b5  16.Bb3  a5  17.a3  Rg8  18.g4  Rg5  19.Rxb2  d5  20.exd5  cxd5  relatively comfortable, with ...Bc8-e6 and ...f6-f5 coming. }
14. h6 { The best try, intending to provoke weaknesses in Black's position. }
14... g5 15. Qd2 Rg8
{ 15...d5  , isn't bad either, and me having rejected it is largely a matter of taste. After  16.Qc3  Rf8  17.Bb3  Black has a choice.  17...dxe4  18.O-O  Be6  19.Rfe1  still gives White some pressure. @@StartFEN@@r1b1kr2/pp2qp1p/2p4P/3p2p1/4P3/1BQP4/PpP2PP1/1R2K2R b Kq - 3 17@@EndFEN@@  17...f5  is a better move, but here too I'd rather play White after  18.O-O  fxe4  19.dxe4  dxe4  20.Qxb2  with compensation for the pawn. The engine though insists all is well after  20...Bd7  .   15...a5!?  is possible too, when  16.Rxb2?  d5  17.Bb3  a4!  wins a piece. So after  15...a5!?  White has to play  16.a4  instead,  16...d5  17.Ba2  dxe4  18.O-O  Qf6  prepares to pick up the h6-pawn with a very messy game. }
16. Rxb2
{ The most sensible move in the position, White simply recaptures the pawn. It doesn't pose too many problems though. }
16... d5 17. Bb3 dxe4 18. O-O Rg6
{ White has to take care now as h6 is bound to fall. } 19. Re1 Bf5
{ White is allowed to take on e4 with the pawn, not with the rook!   If you prefer to avoid the repetition that occurs later on,  19...Rxh6  20.Rxe4  Be6  is a possibility, trying to hold on to the extra pawn. }
20. dxe4 Bd7
{ Black is ready to take on h6 now and castle queenside. White should probably call it a day and fish for a repetition. }
21. Qd4 Rxh6 22. Qh8+ Qf8 23. Qe5+ Qe7 { With a draw by repetition. } *

