{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. Nc3
{ This natural developing move has taken centre stage over the past few years. It is aimed against the move ...g7-g6. }
4... Ng6
{ Leads to a completely different type of game. Suddenly we are facing the Spanish Variation of the Four Knights Game where Black has spent two moves placing the knight on g6, instead of the usual square f6. There are ups and downs to this setup but one thing is for sure, it leads to original games and unexplored territory.   For  4...a6  and  4...g6  , see theInformationals at the beginning of the chapter. }
5. h4
{ Bologan's move and a very logical and direct attempt to refute Black's setup. It questions the manoeuvre ...Ne7-g6 by preparing h4-h5. }
5... Nd4
{ Rare, but the only move that offers Black a good game. White's bishop is hanging on b5 and Black quite literally stops the d2-d4 push from happening. }
6. h5
{ Together with  6.Bc4  , the most consistent move.  White tries to prove that the manoeuvre ...Ne7-g6 is flawed - it is not! }
6... Nf4 7. Nxd4
{ In combination with the next move, the main direction in 6.h5. } 7... exd4
{ The complications after  7...Nxg2+  8.Kf1  exd4  9.Nd5  c6  10.Qg4!  are in White's favour. }
8. Qf3 Bd6
{ 8...Qg5  9.Nd5  Nxd5  10.exd5  Be7  is one of those positions that is close to equal, but just not fully. The pawn on h5 and slight lead in development make that White can still press a bit starting with  11.d3  .   8...g5?  9.hxg6  Nxg6  10.Nd5!  is the big difference with 8.Qg4. }
9. Ne2 Nxe2 { 9...Ne6  10.Bc4!  is awful for Black. } 10. Bxe2 h6
{ An important move to start with.   Instead,  10...O-O  11.h6!  is difficult for Black to face. The pawn will be an annoying presence on h6 after  11...g6  . }
11. d3 a5
{ Very deep! The rook will be entering the game via the a-file. It's part of a waiting game where Black is waiting for White to determine the positioning of the king. Only if White castles kingside do we follow suit.   11...O-O  12.g4!  is very dangerous as the king on g8 is a clear target. The sample line  12...Bb4+  13.Kd1  d5  14.Qg2  dxe4  15.g5  is a clear indication of what is coming.  White must avoid  14.exd5  f5!  .   The direct check  11...Bb4+  12.Kf1  O-O  13.Qg3  is an unpleasant position. }
12. a3
{ Logical, as it stops the check on b4.   12.O-O  Now that White has 'blinked' Black follows suit.  12...O-O  next up the bishop will be removed from d6 in order to get the c8-bishop into the game. The position is very playable. }
12... a4
{ Black takes the chance to take more space on the queenside. Now  a5  is a potential square for the a8-rook to enter the game. The direct  12...Ra6!?  deserves attention as well.   12...O-O  13.g4!  is hard to meet.   And an attempt to solve things by force, with  12...Be5  13.g4  d5  14.exd5  f5  15.gxf5  O-O  is very spirited, but I prefer White following  16.Rg1  Kh8  17.Qe4  Re8  18.Bf4  Qf6  19.Bg4!?  Bxf5  20.Qxf5  Bxf4+  21.Kf1  when play is pretty one-sided. }
13. Qg4
{ Attacking  g7  at an opportune moment, when  13...O-O  runs into  14.Bxh6  .   13.Bd2  This move doesn't have much independent value and is likely to transpose to our main move.  13...Ra6  While the waiting game continues Black brings the rook into the game.  14.Qg4  Be5  15.f4  Bf6  16.Qg3  O-O  Now  17.Qf2  transposes to 13.Qg4 while  17.e5  Be7  18.f5  Bg5  19.O-O-O  d6  is balanced.  @@StartFEN@@2bqk2r/1ppp1pp1/r4b1p/7P/p2pPPQ1/P2P4/1PPBB1P1/R3K2R w KQk - 1 16@@EndFEN@@  16.e5  Backfires after  16...d6  17.Qg3  dxe5  18.fxe5  Bg5!  when Black has the advantage. }
13... Be5 14. f4 Bf6 15. Qg3 { Introducing the threat of e4-e5. } 15... O-O
{ While the engines laugh when seeing this position -declaring equality all over the place- I take things a bit more seriously. Given time, White can make something out of the kingside structure. A future g4-g5 is for example not far off.   That's why I prefer the text move over  15...d6  16.Bd2  which -still 0.00 according to engines- is not that easy for Black. For instance  16...O-O  already leads to trouble following  17.Qh2!  with the idea to take the kingside by storm with g4-g5. With 15...O-O we intend to push d7-d5 in one go, creating direct counterplay. }
16. e5
{ The first move to look it. We are momentarily pushed back but hope to be able to claim that White has in fact overextended.   16.Bd2  Ra6  17.Qf2  transposes to16.Qf2, which will be seen later on. }
16... Be7 17. f5 Bg5
{ The only move to stop both threats of taking on h6 and f5-f6, but a good one! }
18. Bxg5 Qxg5 19. Qxg5 hxg5
{ The endgame is perfectly fine for Black, since e5 is weak. } 20. c3
{ An attempt to set up a broad centre. } 20... dxc3 21. bxc3 Re8 22. d4
{ Optically, this looks wonderful for White, but our next move changes the picture. }
22... d6 { Breaking apart White's centre. } 23. exd6 Bxf5 24. dxc7 Bg4 25. Ra2
Rac8 26. Kf2 Re4 { Maintains equality → c7 will fall next. } *

