{ The only move to stop both threats of taking on h6 and f5-f6, but a good one! }
18. Bxg5 Qxg5 19. Qxg5 hxg5
{ The endgame is perfectly fine for Black, since e5 is weak. } 20. h6 d6
{ Again this move, attacking both e5 and f5. } 21. hxg7 Kxg7 22. f6+ Kg6
{ We will be going for a little stroll!   Obviously not  22...Kg8  23.Rh5!  when Rxg5 and O-O-O next, will get us mated. }
23. Bh5+ Kf5
{ An excellent example of an active king having little to fear in the endgame. }
24. exd6 c5
{ The final accurate move. We are now ready to continue Kf5-e5xd6 and Bc8-e6.   24...cxd6  25.O-O+  Ke6  26.Rae1+  Kd5  27.Re7  would be terrible. }
25. Kd2 Ke5
{ We could stop the line here, but I quite like how it continues which is why I ask you to bear with me! }
26. Rhe1+
{ It is important for White to use the h1-rook for this check.   Instead,  26.Rae1+  Kxd6  27.Re7  Rh8!  followed by Bg4, is awkward. }
26... Kxd6 27. Re7 Be6
{ Black is very comfortable. It is important that White has no time to snatch the pawn on b7. }
28. Rxb7 Rfb8 29. Rxb8 Rxb8
{ Threatens both g5-g4, trapping the bishop, and the pawn on b2. } *

