{ Trying to fix the coordination of the pieces leads to huge complications. }
17... Qg5 18. Rxa8 fxg6
{ Black has again a big threat: Qg5-h4. White has to walk a tight rope in order to survive. After  19.c3  Qh4  20.cxd4  Qh1+  21.Ke2  Qxa1  22.Nb4+  Kd7  23.Rg8  White just about holds. That is because Black can't avoid the perpetual following  23...Qxb2+  24.Kf1  f3  25.Rxg7+  Ke8  26.Rg8+  etc. }
