{ An equally cunning reply!   Note that  13.Bxb5+  Nxb5  14.Nh7  Qh4  15.Nhf6+  gxf6  16.Rxh4  Nxh4  transposes. }
13... Qh4
{ We have to give back our extra queen in order to put an end to White's initiative. }
14. Nhf6+ gxf6 15. Rxh4 Nxh4 16. Bxb5+
{ And once again, we enter complications! } 16... Nxb5 17. a4
{ The point of White's previous move. If the knight moves, c7 will be hanging and, as a consequence, the rook on a8. }
17... Nd4
{ Less convincing, though certainly playable, is  17...c6  18.Nxf6+  Ke7  19.Ng8+!  Ke6  20.axb5  when  20...f5!  is the only move to keep the game going, but White may already be in the driver's seat in any case. }
18. Nxc7+ Kd7 19. Nxa8
{ As usual in this line, this knight won't be coming out of a8 anymore. } 19...
Nxc2 20. Rb1 Nf3
{ Black has a great grip on the position. A sample line is  21.Kg2  Nfe1+  22.Kg3  Nxd3  23.Be3  Kc8  24.Bxa7  Kb7  25.Be3  Nxe3  26.fxe3  Bc5  when the position is approximately even. }
