13. Bxf4 exf4 14. cxd4 O-O-O { A forced and strong piece sacrifice. } 15. fxg4
c6 16. Nc3 f3 { A slick pawn sacrifice, in order to lure the queen to f3. } 17.
Qxf3 hxg4
{ A nice way of opening the h-file. White has no time to take on h8 as the queen is attacked. }
18. Qg2 Rxh1+ 19. Qxh1 Rxd4 { Grabbing a second pawn. } 20. Ke2 Bc5
{ The position is still very unclear but Black is surely fine. The opposite-coloured bishops work in Black's favour here as the initiative is ours. }
21. Rf1
{ The tempting  21.Na4  loses to  21...Rxc4  22.dxc4  Qe3!  as  23.Kd1  Qd3+  24.Ke1  Bd6!  is mating on g3. }
21... Rd6
{ This contains a devilish trick. After  22.Rxf7?  Black switches the rook to the other side of the board with  22...Rh6  followed by ...g4-g3 with a winning initiative.   Black could also have tried to force a draw with  21...Rxc4  22.Qh8+  Kc7  23.Rxf7+  Kb6  24.dxc4  Qe3+  25.Kd1  Qd3+  26.Ke1  Qe3+  but we would have to remember a lot of moves as the line continues with  27.Ne2  Bb4+  28.Kf1  Qd3!  29.Qh4  , with the idea to intercept with check on  f2  , if Black picks up the knight on  e2  ,  29...Qb1+!  30.Kg2  Qxe4+  and White can't avoid the perpetual. Why to go through all this trouble? }
*

