[White "Chapter 6: The f7 'weakness' - 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.h4 Nd4 6.Bc4"]
[Black "Cozio Defence 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.h4 Nd4 - 6.Bc4 #41"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. Nc3
{ This natural developing move has taken centre stage over the past few years. It is aimed against the move ...g7-g6. }
4... Ng6
{ Leads to a completely different type of game. Suddenly we are facing the Spanish Variation of the Four Knights Game where Black has spent two moves placing the knight on g6, instead of the usual square f6. There are ups and downs to this setup but one thing is for sure, it leads to original games and unexplored territory.   For  4...a6  and  4...g6  , see theInformationals at the beginning of Chapter  5. }
5. h4
{ Bologan's move and a very logical and direct attempt to refute Black's setup. It questions the manoeuvre ...Ne7-g6 by preparing h4-h5. }
5... Nd4
{ Rare, but the only move that offers Black a good game. White's bishop is hanging on b5 and Black quite literally stops the d2-d4 push from happening. }
6. Bc4
{ The most logical reply. White preserves the bishop and gives it a good view on the f7-pawn. }
6... h5
{ After @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n3n1/1B2p3/4P2P/2N2N2/PPPP1PP1/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...h5  ,  6.d4  is a strong reply, but by including the moves  5...Nd4  6.Bc4  , the text move becomes a much stronger option now. White no longer has the d2-d4 push.   6...c6  7.h5  Nf4  8.Nxd4  exd4  9.Qf3!  followed by Nc3-e2 is no solution for Black.   6...Bc5  7.d3  O-O  8.Bg5  is also quite awkard. After  8...Be7  9.Nd5  Black's position doesn't inspire much confidence.   Undoubtedly the prettiest way of going wrong is  6...d5  7.Nxd5  Bg4  8.Nxd4!  Bxd1  9.Bb5+  c6  10.Nxc6!  and White wins, as after  10...bxc6  11.Bxc6+  the sacrificed queen is regained with interest. }
7. Ng5
{ The big question to answer, as this knight jump looks very awkward for Black. }
7... d5
{ A surprising thrust, yet essential to keep the game going.   7...Ne6  would not be in keeping with the position. We also shouldn't overdo it with our knight maneuvering! }
8. Nxd5 { White's only move! } 8... Nxh4
{ Removing the defender of the knight on g5. } 9. d3 Nxg2+
{ As the line  9...Bg4  10.f3  Nxg2+  11.Kf2!  shows, it is important to start with 9...Nxg2+, when the king does not have access to the f2 square. }
10. Kf1 Bg4
{ We have before us the type of position where any wrong move can lose the game - for either side!   Inversing the move order doesn't work as  10...Nf4  11.Bxf4  Bg4  12.Qxg4!  is a very convincing queen sacrifice. Following  12...hxg4  13.Rxh8  exf4  14.Nh7!  White should win. }
11. f3
{ This makes Black's position once again look precarious. Both the knight on g2 and the bishop on g4 are in trouble. }
11... Nf4
{ The saving resource. The knight on g5 proves vulnerable too. In this razor-sharp position we will have a look at no less than six moves! }
12. Nxf7 { White's best chance. } 12... Bxf3
{ We should not get involved in  12...Kxf7  13.Nxf4+  when 14.hxg4 next gives White a huge advantage. }
13. Nxd8 Bxd1 14. Bxf4 { Not White's best option. } 14... Be2+ 15. Kf2 exf4 16.
Nxb7 Rb8 { Material is equal, but the position is not! } 17. c3 Rxb7 18. cxd4
Bg4
{ Black is in good shape with the two bishops and outside passed pawns.   After for instance  19.Nxf4  Rxb2+  20.Kg3  g5  21.Ng6  Rh6  The most ambitious move.   A very pretty line, leading to a draw by perpetual check, is  21...Bc8  22.Nxh8  h4+  23.Kf3  g4+  24.Kf4  Bh6+  . White can't avoid the checks after  25.Ke5  Bg7+  26.Kd5  Bb7+  27.Ke6  Bc8+  which is quite remarkable!  22.Nxf8  the best winning attempt is  22...Be2!?  when White has to find  23.Rhb1  h4+  24.Kf2  Rf6  25.Kg1  to stay in the game. Even so, I'd still take Black following  25...Rxb1+  26.Rxb1  Kxf8  as Black's outside passed pawns are looking impressive! }
*

