10. O-O O-O 11. a4
{ Taking away the a3-square from the queen so that the c1-bishop can enter the game. }
11... d6
{ We go for the same setup that Magnus Carlsen chose, but without allowing the improvement on move 10 in his game.   11...a5!?  is an alternative on which Leela and Stockfish disagree. The argument arises after  12.Be3  Bc5  13.Bxc5  Qxc5  which Stockfish believes to be pretty bad for Black. I'm in the middle, thinking that after a line like  14.Rfe1  d6  15.Rad1  Rd8  16.g3  we haven't fully equalized yet at all, while White's play is easy. And @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p1p1ppp/2p3n1/p1q5/P3P3/2NQ4/1PP1BPPP/R3R1K1 b - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Nf4  15.Qg3  Nxe2+  16.Rxe2  isn't pretty for Black either.   11...Re8  Feels wrong, because after  12.Kh1  d6  13.f4  , we can no longer counter with  13...f5  . }
12. a5 Qc7
{ 12...Qd8  13.Be3  is a slightly worse version of things, as the queen is well placed on c7 now. }
13. Be3 { 13.f4  Bd7  14.Be3  transposes to 13.Be3. } 13... Bd7
{ Again this modest-looking move! By connecting the rooks, the move b7-b5/6 becomes available now. Other moves don't do the trick.   13...Ne5  is too ambitious. The simple  14.Qd2  f5  15.f4  Ng4  16.Bxg4  fxg4  17.Qf2  gives White a big advantage. White has to avoid  @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq1b1pp/2pp4/P3np2/4P3/2N1B3/1PPQBPPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Bf4  Ng6!  which was fine for Black in Abreu-Rodi, Maraba 2016. If White wants to keep his bishop alive, f5-f4 will have to be allowed.   13...Be6  is a bit clumsy, and forces Black, after  14.f4  to push  14...f5  after which  15.g3  gives White a pleasant edge. }
14. f4
{ White has gotten in the f2-f4 push but at a price. Pushing a4-a5 is not very desirable on the queenside, as it will ease Black's task of counterplay connected to b7-b5. White's a-pawn was doing a much better job on a4! }
14... Rfe8
{ 14...b6!?  can be considered as well. But I like our strategy of awaiting developments. We get into 'counter mode' waiting in ambush for our opponents to make an error. }
15. Bd4
{ A waiting move which does stop Black from playing Be7-f6 in the near future. }
15... b5 { Again this freeing advance. } 16. axb6 axb6 17. Rad1 d5
{ Making use of the fact that by opening the h2-b8 diagonal, f4 is a target. }
18. Qd2 dxe4 19. f5
{ Initiating very sharp play.   19.Nxe4  Bh4!?  20.Bf3  Rad8  is less critical. }
19... Nh4 20. f6 Bd6 21. Qg5 { Too direct. Black is much better now. } 21...
Ng6 22. fxg7 Bf4 23. Qf6 Re6 24. Qf5 Re7 25. Qf6 Ra5
{ Threatening to trap the queen with Ra5-f5 next. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 7: An Intriguing Mixture - 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.d4"]
[Black "Cozio Defence 4.Nc3 Ng6 5.d4 - 8.Bc4 Qb6 9.Qd3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this course we will have an in-depth look at the Cozio Defence, named after Carlo Cozio, Count of Montiglio and Salabue @@StartBracket@@Italy, 1715-1780@@EndBracket@@. After publishing his manuscript Il giuoco degli scacchi in 1766, where he explained the ideas behind 3...Nge7, this line received his name. It all starts with the following moves: }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez remains White's main answer. The abundance of opening theory in the Berlin Defence  3...Nf6  or Morphy Defence  3...a6  can be overwhelming. It can therefore be interesting to surprise the opponent with a line that is much less known. And one that is, perhaps undeservedly so, regarded as dubious. }
3... Nge7
{ The move that this course is all about. Black chooses an unusual way of development but one that does carry some logic. In case White is ever to take on c6, Black will have the option of recapturing with the knight. }
4. Nc3
{ This natural developing move has taken centre stage over the past few years. It is aimed against the move ...g7-g6. }
4... Ng6
{ Leads to a completely different type of game. Suddenly we are facing the Spanish Variation of the Four Knights Game where Black has spent two moves placing the knight on g6, instead of the usual square f6. There are ups and downs to this setup but one thing is for sure, it leads to original games and unexplored territory.   For  4...a6  and  4...g6  , see theInformationals at the beginning of Chapter  5. }
5. d4
{ The most obvious move, White opens up the position to make the lead in development count. }
5... exd4 6. Nxd4
{ We have before us a strange blend of the Scotch Four Knights variation - a very weird mixture! Here I will provide two options for Black. }
6... Nxd4
{ After a mere 6 moves we have already landed in a very obscure spot in opening theory. Indeed the direction we are taking here is relatively new.   I like  6...Bb4  less, as White has many promising continuations. For instance  7.O-O  O-O  8.f4!?  The direct approach.  8...a6  9.Bc4!   9.Be2  d5!  is Black's imaginative idea, with very interesting complications. Alas, we won't get the chance!  9...b5  10.Bd5  Nge7  11.f5  Here, in order not to get overrun, Black has to go for  11...Nxd5   11...Bxc3  12.bxc3  Nxd5  13.exd5  Nxd4  14.f6!  is very strong.  12.Nxd5  Bc5  13.Be3  f6   13...Bxd4  14.Bxd4  f6  15.e5!  is surprisingly strong. After  15...fxe5  16.Be3  d6  17.Qh5  followed by f5-f6, Black is in deep trouble.  14.Nxc6  Bxe3+  15.Nxe3  dxc6  and this position looks a bit sad to me. White can try to play it sharp here with  16.Qg4  , or just play the solid  16.Re1  in both cases with a risk-free advantage.   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppp1ppp/2n3n1/1B6/1b1NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be3  Normal development will do as well.  8...Nce7  Aiming for the ...d7-d5 break.   8...Re8  9.Nde2  is slightly better for White as well.  9.f4  c6   9...d5  10.f5  Ne5  11.Qh5  is dangerous as well, with Rad1 coming next.  10.Be2  d5  11.f5!  Ne5  12.f6!  gxf6  13.Qe1  dxe4  14.Qg3+  N5g6  15.Nxe4  Black's position looks bad. Do investigate these lines further if you want to use 6...Bb4 as an alternative to our main lines. With the above lines I have wanted to illustrate my reasoning behind not making it my main recommendation.   In the spirit of the Scotch would be the move  6...Bc5  , and  7.Be3  Bxd4  8.Bxd4  O-O  has been played by some strong players. It is pretty dubious though, and I am also not certain what it is Black is hoping for in this line. Following  9.Be3  d6  10.Qd2  a6  11.Be2  f5  12.f4!  fxe4  13.O-O-O  Nh4  14.g4  White already had an overwhelming position in Ghaem Maghami-Short, Teheran 2013, which was eventually drawn on move 36. }
7. Qxd4 c6
{ A pleasant move to make. We hit the bishop and this pawn will do a great job in the future keeping the enemy knight from d5. Apart from that, ...Qd8-b6 is prepared. }
8. Be2 { The best square. Others are less promising. } 8... Qb6 9. Qd3
{ Without a doubt the best move in the position. } 9... Be7
{ We continue as usual, developing the bishop and castling kingside.   More active is  9...Bc5  but after  10.O-O  Black is vulnerable to Nc3-a4, allowing White to claim a plus.   The World Champion himself made an appearance in this line as well. During an online chess event hosted by the St. Louis Chess Club, he continued  9...d6  10.O-O  Be7  11.Be3  Qxb2  12.f4  Qa3  13.Bd4  O-O  14.Rad1  Qa5  and Black was better in Dominguez Perez-Carlsen, Lichess Blitz 2020. Play can be improved upon on various occasions, but most notable on move 10, when @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/pp3ppp/1qpp2n1/8/4P3/2NQ4/PPP1BPPP/R1B1K2R w KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10.h4  is a huge improvement. }
10. O-O O-O 11. a4
{ Taking away the a3-square from the queen so that the c1-bishop can enter the game. }
11... d6
{ We go for the same setup that Magnus Carlsen chose, but without allowing the improvement on move 10 in his game.   11...a5!?  is an alternative on which Leela and Stockfish disagree. The argument arises after  12.Be3  Bc5  13.Bxc5  Qxc5  which Stockfish believes to be pretty bad for Black. I'm in the middle, thinking that after a line like  14.Rfe1  d6  15.Rad1  Rd8  16.g3  we haven't fully equalized yet at all, while White's play is easy. And @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p1p1ppp/2p3n1/p1q5/P3P3/2NQ4/1PP1BPPP/R3R1K1 b - - 1 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Nf4  15.Qg3  Nxe2+  16.Rxe2  isn't pretty for Black either.   11...Re8  Feels wrong, because after  12.Kh1  d6  13.f4  , we can no longer counter with  13...f5  . }
12. a5 Qc7
{ 12...Qd8  13.Be3  is a slightly worse version of things, as the queen is well placed on c7 now. }
13. Be3 { 13.f4  Bd7  14.Be3  transposes to 13.Be3. } 13... Bd7
{ Again this modest-looking move! By connecting the rooks, the move b7-b5/6 becomes available now. Other moves don't do the trick.   13...Ne5  is too ambitious. The simple  14.Qd2  f5  15.f4  Ng4  16.Bxg4  fxg4  17.Qf2  gives White a big advantage. White has to avoid  @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq1b1pp/2pp4/P3np2/4P3/2N1B3/1PPQBPPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Bf4  Ng6!  which was fine for Black in Abreu-Rodi, Maraba 2016. If White wants to keep his bishop alive, f5-f4 will have to be allowed.   13...Be6  is a bit clumsy, and forces Black, after  14.f4  to push  14...f5  after which  15.g3  gives White a pleasant edge. }
14. f4
{ White has gotten in the f2-f4 push but at a price. Pushing a4-a5 is not very desirable on the queenside, as it will ease Black's task of counterplay connected to b7-b5. White's a-pawn was doing a much better job on a4! }
14... Rfe8
{ 14...b6!?  can be considered as well. But I like our strategy of awaiting developments. We get into 'counter mode' waiting in ambush for our opponents to make an error. }
15. Bd4
{ A waiting move which does stop Black from playing Be7-f6 in the near future. }
15... b5 { Again this freeing advance. } 16. axb6 axb6 17. Rad1 d5
{ Making use of the fact that by opening the h2-b8 diagonal, f4 is a target. }
18. Qd2 dxe4 19. f5
{ Initiating very sharp play.   19.Nxe4  Bh4!?  20.Bf3  Rad8  is less critical. }
19... Nh4 20. f6 Bd6 21. Kh1
{ It is remarkable how in sharp positions, it is often a subtle king move like this one that is the best move. }
21... Nf5 22. Bg1
{ Threatens to win a piece with g2-g4. It looks grim for Black, but the saga continues. }
22... Rad8 23. g4 e3 { Opening the long diagonal. } 24. Qd3 Nd4
{ I am running out of exclaims! The knight is sacrificed on d4, to gain a tempo on the queen. }
25. Qxd4 c5 { Now it all becomes clear. The bishop will soon land on c6. } 26.
Qc4 Bc6+ 27. Nd5 Qb7 { Prepares b6-b5 to overload the queen. White is lost! } *

