{ Again this modest-looking move! By connecting the rooks, the move b7-b5/6 becomes available now. Other moves don't do the trick.   13...Ne5  is too ambitious. The simple  14.Qd2  f5  15.f4  Ng4  16.Bxg4  fxg4  17.Qf2  gives White a big advantage. White has to avoid  @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppq1b1pp/2pp4/P3np2/4P3/2N1B3/1PPQBPPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15.Bf4  Ng6!  which was fine for Black in Abreu-Rodi, Maraba 2016. If White wants to keep his bishop alive, f5-f4 will have to be allowed.   13...Be6  is a bit clumsy, and forces Black, after  14.f4  to push  14...f5  after which  15.g3  gives White a pleasant edge. }
14. f4
{ White has gotten in the f2-f4 push but at a price. Pushing a4-a5 is not very desirable on the queenside, as it will ease Black's task of counterplay connected to b7-b5. White's a-pawn was doing a much better job on a4! }
14... Rfe8
{ 14...b6!?  can be considered as well. But I like our strategy of awaiting developments. We get into 'counter mode' waiting in ambush for our opponents to make an error. }
15. Bf3
{ The most obvious move. White tries to tighten the grip on the position by placing the bishop on f3. }
15... b5 { Time to show we can also sting a bit! } 16. axb6 axb6 17. Rxa8 Rxa8
{ Having, next to a pair of knights, also exchanged a pair of rooks, White's space advantage has lost most of its significance. We can follow up by rerouting the badly placed knight on g6, first to f8 and perhaps later to e6/d7 while another option is to push b6-b5, simply to improve our queenside structure. And by recapturing on a8, we reached the end of this course.  Next up, I added a few model games for instructive purposes. Combined with the theoretical knowledge we have gathered, that should make us good to go! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Zukertort - Anderssen, Breslau 1865"]
[Result "*"]

{ Adolf Anderssen was one of the first top players to use the Cozio Defence regularly, unfortunately not with great results. In this game, Anderssen gets bluffed in beautiful fashion by another giant from the past, Johannes Zukertort. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7 4. c3 d6
{ 4...d5  ishow we reply to White's 4th move. Sources say Anderssen had issues with his internet connection before the game and could therefore not access the Chessable move trainer. Anderssen's move is by no means bad, but the setup is rather passive and doesn't promise Black equal chances. }
5. d4 Bd7 6. O-O
{ 6.d5!?  Nb8  7.Bxd7+  Nxd7  8.c4  is an interesting strategy as well, taking play into King's Indian waters. The exchange of light-squared bishops should favor White here. }
6... Ng6 7. Ng5
{ The good old times! It is not difficult to foresee what Zukertort had in mind with his last move. Objectively speaking, White throws away his advantage with this move. Almost any reasonable developing move would have kept it. }
7... h6
{ A perfectly fine reply.   Equally good is  7...Be7  and it's not clear what White should do. I assume Zukertort wanted to play  8.Qh5  but here  8...exd4  is more than sufficient. }
8. Nxf7 { Given the final result, it is hard to argue with this decision! }
8... Kxf7 9. Bc4+
{ After this check the game reaches its climax. Where to move the king?   147 years later,  9.f4  was tried, and after  9...exd4  10.Qh5  Qf6  11.f5  White had a promising position in Gislason-Thorfinnsson, Kopavogur 2012. But @@StartFEN@@r2q1b1r/pppb1kp1/2np2np/1B2p3/3PPP2/2P5/PP4PP/RNBQ1RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...exf4!  10.Bxf4  Nxf4  11.Rxf4+  Kg8  refutes White's play. }
9... Ke7
{ Or @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/pppb2p1/3p1qnp/4nP1Q/2BpP3/2P5/PP4PP/RNB2RK1 w - - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Be2  d3  14.Bd1  Kd8!  -out of the pin-  15.fxg6  Qxg6  with a huge advantage for Black. }
10. Qh5 Qe8
{ Anderssen chooses to go down in style.   Zukertort points out that  10...Be8  11.Bg5+  hxg5  12.Qxg5+  Kd7  13.Qf5+  Ke7  14.Qe6  would have led to mate as well. }
11. Qg5+ hxg5 12. Bxg5# { Boden's Mate! A nice display by Zukertort. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Fraser - Steinitz, Dundee 1867"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played in the international tournament of Dundee in 1867. Steinitz took second place behind Gustav Neumann and his opponent in this game, George Brunton Fraser, had a considerably harder time in Dundee. This game, in a way, is exemplary for that. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7 4. c3 d5 5. Nxe5 dxe4 6. Qa4
{ We know that this isnot the way to go, but at the time, this variation was in the early stages of development.   After this game, attention shifted to  6.d4  but as it turns out, Black need not fear  6...exd3  7.Qf3  Be6  8.Nxc6  Nxc6  9.Bxc6+  bxc6  10.Qxc6+  Bd7  with an excellent position. Three years later, the game Wisker-Burn, London 1870, continued  11.Qf3  Bd6  12.O-O  O-O  13.Qxd3  Rb8  14.Qc2  Qh4  15.f4  Rfe8  16.c4  Bc5+  17.Kh1  Re1  18.Nd2  Qf2  and White resigned, just in time before mate!   It would take the genius of Fischer to 'refute' the line 100 years later. After  6.Qe2  Qd5  7.Nxc6  Nxc6  8.d4  Bf5  9.Nd2  White was clearly better in Fischer-Shipman, New York 1971. For decades this game was thought to be the end of the line. Fast-forward to today and we play6...Be6! instead of 6...Qd5, giving Black an excellent game. }
6... Qd5 7. Nxc6
{ The above mentioned Amos Burn had some real success with the Cozio in those days. Let's see another spectacular example:  7.f4  Bd7   7...Be6!  8.Na3  O-O-O!  is myrecommendation in the course. The queensac after  9.Bc4  Nxe5  10.Bxd5  Nd3+  11.Kf1  Nxd5  is terrific for Black.  8.Nxd7  Kxd7  9.Bc4  Qf5  10.Qb3  White, over the next couple of moves, wastes too much time, which should have been spend on developing.  10...Ng6  11.Qxb7  Nxf4  12.O-O  Qc5+  13.d4  Qxc4   13...exd3+  14.Kh1  Nh3!!  15.gxh3  Qxc4  is winning, as  16.Qxa8  Qe4+  17.Kg1  Bc5+  is mating @@StartBracket@@and winning the queen, just to be sure@@EndBracket@@.  The simple  14.Bxf4  would have left Black's position in utter ruins.  But White went for  14.Qxa8  Bc5!  Burn's interpertation of Anderssen's Immortal Game.  15.Qxh8  Nxd4!  White's lack of development comes to his doom. The main threat is Nf3+ followed by mate on f1.  16.Be3  Qe2!  Powerplay.  17.Qxg7  Nf3+  18.gxf3  White resigned, Blackburne-Burn, London 1870. It is mate in 3 starting with  18...Bxe3+  19.Kh1  Qxf1+  20.Qg1  Qxg1 }
7... Nxc6 8. Bxc6+
{ Too compliant.   8.c4  Qe6  9.Bxc6+  bxc6  as in Paulsen-Blackburne, Baden-Baden 1870, doesn't improve the position much, and brought Blackburne a nice victory.   Relatively best is  8.O-O  Bd7  9.d4  exd3  10.Re1+  Be7  11.Qc4  , trying to escape into an endgame. }
8... Qxc6
{ While this works out splendidly in the game, it is hard to say which recapture on c6 is best.   Steinitz's big rival, Adolf Anderssen, played  8...bxc6  9.O-O  and now  9...Bd6!  gives Black a great position.   Anderssen continued  9...Bd7  10.Re1  f5  and now  11.d3!  Qxd3  12.Na3  would have given White interesting compensation. Instead,  11.f3  Qd3  passed the advantage over to Black. After a few more adventures the game ended in Black's favour @@StartBracket@@Riemann-Anderssen, Breslau 1876@@EndBracket@@.  10.Re1  The move that I assume stopped Anderssen from playing 9...Bd6. The point is simple and strong.  10...O-O!  11.Qxe4  Qh5!  12.h3  Bf5  White is lost as he is about to be run over. }
9. Qxc6+ bxc6 10. O-O
{ Already the decisive mistake.   It was imperrative to prevent the bishop from reaching d3. The only way to do so is  10.b3!  so that  10...Ba6  can be met with  11.c4  . }
10... Ba6 11. Re1 Bd3 { Good luck getting rid of that bishop! } 12. c4
{ Perhaps  12.b3  O-O-O  13.Ba3  is a better defence but regardless, White's position should be lost. }
12... f5 13. b3 Bc5
{ While this doesn't spoil much,  13...O-O-O  was stronger, not yet determining the position of the bishop. In case of  14.Ba3  Black forces a winning rook endgame with  14...Bxb1  15.Bxf8  Rhxf8  16.Raxb1  Rxd2  . }
14. Bb2
{ 14.Ba3!?  was a better defence, though it's clear Black is in full control after  14...Bxa3  15.Nxa3  O-O-O  . }
14... O-O-O 15. Bxg7
{ This game was played 153 years ago, so the players deserve some leeway. This move, however, does ask for trouble.   15.Nc3  was the answer but at the risk of repeating myself, Black is of course calling all the shots. }
15... Rhg8 16. Bc3 Rd6
{ The famous combination that Steinitz played on the next move was actually already available here. With  16...Rxg2+!  he could have decided the issue on the spot. }
17. b4 Rxg2+
{ The slow  17...Rdg6  18.g3  Bd6  does the trick as well, but this is the romantic era of chess! }
18. Kxg2 Rg6+ 19. Kh1 Bxf2
{ A rook up, White is helpless against ...e4-e3 followed by ...Bd3-e4. } 20.
Na3 e3 21. h4 e2
{ 21...Be4+  22.Kh2  f4  also does the job and maybe even a bit faster. But while engines see lines like  23.Rg1  Rh6!  instantly, a human can easily overlook that after  24.Rg8+  Kb7  White is helpless. }
22. Be5 Rg4 23. Kh2 f4 24. Nc2 f3 { The mating net is closing. } 25. Bf6 Bxc2
{ Fraser resigned. Steinitz got a nice advantage from the opening, converted it to a huge endgame advantage and when the bishop landed on d3 the game was essentially over. The nice finale with the rook sac on g2 made this game one of Steinitz's classics. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Hort - Larsen, Bristol (rapid) 1979"]
[Result "*"]

{ The players need no introduction. Both Bent Larsen and Vlastimil Hort were among the top players in the world in the '60s and '70s. In 1979 they played a rapid match which was televised by the BBC. Larsen won the match 3-2  (four draws)  and we will have a look at game 3. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ It is not surprising to see a player like Bent Larsen play the Cozio. Larsen often preferred the original over the beaten tracks. Larsen enriched the chess world with countless interesting ideas and in the Cozio there is plenty of room for exploration. In short, it fits his style. }
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ Asmentioned earlier in this course, I dislike  5...g6  because of  6.Nxc6!  when  6...bxc6  7.Qd4!  forces  7...Rg8  which is a very ugly move to make. }
6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qe3 Bb4+
{ This is a pretty serious inaccuracy. We prefer to develop to a different square with 7...Be7. The idea is to keep the b4-square available so that a future Nb1-c3-d5 can be met with ...Nc6-b4, exchanging knights. }
8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O
{ 9.Bd2!  d6  10.O-O-O  is a more ambitious and also much stronger setup. White's play is straightforward as the kingside will be ambushed next with f2-f4, g2-g4, etc., simply pushing the kingside pawns forward. It is very hard for Black to create counterplay. }
9... d6 10. Nd5 Bc5 11. Qg3
{ The position is still very pleasant for White. He has a space advantage and the better pieces. }
11... Kh8 12. Bd2 Nd4
{ The engine suggests  12...a5  13.Rad1  Bd7  14.Bc3  f6  followed by ...Nc6-e5, which does seem to create some kind of block. Still though, if we continue the line a few more moves, with  15.Be2  Ne5  16.Kh1  c6  17.Ne3  White is ready to play f2-f4 and is still very much in charge. I like the move played by Larsen, especially from a practical viewpoint. He wants to initiate exchanges and reroute the knight to the better square  e6  . }
13. Bd3
{ Interesting is  13.Bc3  with the idea that White wins back the piece after  13...c6  14.Rfd1!  and Black is actually in serious trouble. A very instructive variation is  14...cxd5  15.Bxd4  Bxd4  16.Rxd4  dxe4  17.Qxd6  Qxd6  18.Rxd6  Bf5  19.Rad1  e3  20.c3  exf2+  21.Kxf2  when play has entered an endgame.  Just how bad is this endgame for Black? The answer is: very bad! The reason is the difference in piece play. White's rooks dominate, the king can easily enter the game and with Bd7 coming, Black will soon be targeted on the 7th rank. }
13... c6 14. Nf4 Ne6
{ Not only does Larsen offer an exchange of knights, but Black also plays with the idea of exchanging queens on g5, with ...Qd8-g5. }
15. Bc3
{ This allows Black to neutralize White's advantage.   White had two options that were more promising:  15.Ne2!?  keeping the knigts on the board and stopping ...Qd8-g5. Now  15...Bb6  16.Bc3  f6  17.Rfe1  Nc5  18.Nf4  remains unpleasant for Black.   15.Rad1  does allow  15...Qg5  but following  16.Qxg5  Nxg5  17.b4  Bb6  18.Nd5!  White keeps some initiative even in the endgame. }
15... Qg5 16. Qxg5 Nxg5
{ We have seen this throughout this course: when the queens come off, we should reevaluate the importance of space. The more pieces come off, the less importance it has. }
17. Rae1 Ne6 { Larsen has comfortably equalized. } 18. Bd2 Nxf4 19. Bxf4 Be6
20. e5 dxe5 21. Bxe5 Rad8 22. a3 Rfe8 23. h3 Kg8 24. Re2 Bd5
{ Draw agreed. The position has indeed dried up considerably! While this may not be the most exciting game out there, I did like the struggle in the opening/early middlegame where a small mistake @@StartBracket@@6...Bb4@@EndBracket@@ landed Black in big trouble. Larsen's ...Nd4-e6 and ...c7-c6 worked miracles to take the sting out of the position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Murey - Dreev, Moscow 1989"]
[Result "*"]

{ Jacob Murey is a Russian-born Israeli grandmaster who, perhaps most notably, was the second of Viktor Kortchnoi in his 1978 World Championship match against Anatoly Karpov. Dreev was something of a child prodigy, becoming World Champion under 16 and being taught by the late top trainer Mark Dvoretsky. He remains one of the strongest grandmasters of Russia today. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7
{ Dreev often used the Cozio in his younger years. The reason we haven't seen him much throughout the course is because within the Cozio he often chose different lines than the ones we are playing. }
4. Nc3 g6 { 4...Ng6  is our preferredoption here. } 5. d4 exd4 6. Nd5
{ This is generally considered the most critical way of playing but I believe it is not. The reason I did not recommend 4...g6, is  6.Nxd4!  Bg7  7.Be3  O-O  8.Nxc6!  bxc6  9.Ba4  which I believe to give White a significant advantage. The main issue is that Black can't free himself with  9...d5  because of  10.Bc5! }
6... Bg7 7. Bg5
{ We enter forced play. Black's next move is obliged as White threatens to win material by taking on c6. }
7... h6 8. Bf6 Bxf6 9. Nxf6+ Kf8 10. Nxd4
{ As I explained inChapter 5,  10.Qd2!?  is stronger, and only after  10...Kg7  does White play  11.Nxd4  .   Black should play  10...d5!  instead, which seems to be holding. }
10... Kg7
{ 10...Nf5!  is the reason for the move order explained on move  10. I refer to the firstInformational in Chapter 5 for a detailed explanation. }
11. Qd2
{ Murey's brilliant innovation. Throughout his career, Murey came up with a number of astonishing discoveries. One example is in the Petroff, where after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.d4  Nxe4  4.Bd3  he came up with the shocker  4...Nc6!  intending to meet  5.Bxe4  with  5...d5  and 6...e4, to win back the piece. It is clear that such a creative mind must have been an excellent inclusion in Kortchnoi's World Championship team. }
11... Ng8
{ Certainly not a pleasant move to make!   The point is that after  11...Kxf6  12.Qc3!  the king is in mortal danger.  12...Nxd4  13.Qxd4+  Ke6  14.Bc4+  d5  15.exd5+  Kd7  16.O-O-O  is simply lost, with the king stuck in the centre, and  12...Ne5  13.f4!  also doesn't inspire confidence. }
12. Nd5
{ 12.Nxg8  Rxg8  13.O-O-O  was likely the stronger option. White is completely mobilized and Black certainly can't say the same. After for instance  13...Qf6  14.Bxc6  dxc6  15.f3  with a big and stable advantage. }
12... Nf6 13. Nc3
{ Very instructive! White wants to keep the pieces on the board. The knight that made the journey from c3 to d5 and f6, now returns via the same route!   13.Nxf6  Qxf6  14.Bxc6  is still possible, but two@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ tempi down compared to the line above. }
13... Nh5
{ After  13...Qe7  , the pawn sacrifice  14.O-O!  is very strong. Accepting the pawn leads to trouble following  14...Nxe4  15.Nxe4  Qxe4  16.Nxc6  dxc6  17.Qc3+  Kh7  18.Rfe1  Qf5  19.Bd3  Qg5  20.f4!  Qd8  21.Bc4  where Black still has the extra pawn but White has all the fun. }
14. g4
{ 14.Be2!  is excellent too, because  14...Qg5  15.Ndb5!  reminds Black of the weakness on c7. }
14... Qg5
{ This speeds up the end. The only chance lays in  14...Nf4  but the position is dire nevertheless.  15.Qxf4  Nxd4  16.Qe5+  Qf6  17.Qxf6+  Kxf6  18.Nd5+  Ke5  19.Nxc7  Nxc2+  20.Kd2  Nxa1  21.Nxa8  leads to a situation where the a8-knight will jump to safety via  c7  , but the a1-knight is unable to do the same. Black's best shot is  21...d5  22.Rxa1  Bxg4  23.Nc7  dxe4  to try and save a draw with two pawns for the knight. }
15. Qxg5 { 15.Bxc6  would also have won immediately. } 15... hxg5 16. Bxc6 dxc6
17. gxh5 Rxh5
{ A piece down in an endgame, Dreev could now safely have resigned. Despite the game stretching out for another 13 moves, the final result was never in doubt. }
18. f3 g4 19. Kf2 Rh3 20. fxg4 Bxg4 21. Rag1 Rd8 22. Rxg4 Rxd4 23. Kg2 Re3 24.
Rf1 Rb4 25. Rf2 f5 26. Rgf4 fxe4 27. a3 Rd4 28. Ne2 Rd7 29. Ng3 Re7 30. Rg4 Kh7
31. Rff4
{ Dreev resigned. After e4 falls, the technical job is very easy. An important game for the development of the Cozio. Murey's 11.Qd2!! is an amazing innovation that caused an immediate collapse to the opponent. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Bok - Timman, Wijk aan Zee 2014"]
[Result "*"]

{ Benjamin Bok is a grandmaster from the new generation in the Netherlands. He combines excellent calculation skills with a very healthy approach to the game. His opponent, Jan Timman, was one of the best players in the world for decades and frankly, needs no introduction! }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nge7 5. c3 g6
{ Through a different move order we have reached a position that is familiar to us again. I won't repeat the analysis we have seen earlier but would rather refer toChapter 4 for the details on everything related to 4.0-0. }
6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 b5 8. Bc2 d5 9. exd5 Nb4 10. Bb3 Nbxd5 11. O-O Bg7 12. Re1
{ Later that year, the game Adams - J. Van Foreest, Isle of Man 2014, continued  12.Bg5  Qd6  13.Nbd2  Bf5  14.Re1  O-O  15.Rc1  Rae8  16.Ne4  Bxe4  17.Rxe4  f6  18.Bf4  Qd8  19.Bxc7  Qa8  20.Rxe7  Rxe7  21.Rc5  and Black resigned.   As we know from earlier in this course, weimprove on this game with  12...h6  , with dynamic equality. }
12... O-O 13. Bg5 Nf6
{ A strong new idea at the time. The reason Bok was happy to get to this position is that the move  13...Qd6  was universally played before this game, getting out of the pin. After  14.Nbd2  Bf5  15.Rc1  White has a pleasant advantage here. 13...Nf6! is a much more effective way of meeting 13.Bg5. }
14. Nc3 Bb7 15. d5
{ It is understandable that White wants to prevent Black from setting up a blockade on the d5-square.   15.Ne5  Nf5  starts active play against the d-pawn. }
15... h6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qd2 Bg7
{ Not  17...Kg7  as White is happy to temporarily sacrifice a pawn after  18.Ne4!  Nxd5  19.Nc5  with winning compensation. If we make a few more moves,  19...Bc6  20.Rad1  Ne7  21.Qc1  Qc8  22.Nd4  Bxd4  23.Rxd4  Nf5  24.Rd3  , it is easy to see why. White's pieces are incredibly dominant. }
18. Rad1 c5
{ A very ambitious move, and perhaps not what the position demanded.   The straightforward  18...Nf5  intending to plant the knight on d6, would give Black a small but comfortable edge. Look at that bishop on g7! }
19. dxc6
{ Not asking the critical question!   White should have gone  19.d6  Nf5  20.Ne5  when play gets very double-edged. A sample line is  20...c4  21.Bc2  Re8  22.f4  Qb6+  23.Qf2  Qxf2+  24.Kxf2  Rad8  when there seems to be no immediate knock-out blow for White, but the pressure is obviously on. }
19... Nxc6
{ A big error in return.   The endgame after  19...Qxd2  20.Rxd2  Nxc6  is slightly better for Black because of the bishop pair, though White should be able to hold without too much trouble. }
20. Qc2
{ It looks tempting to hit d8 and g6 at the same time, yet c2 is not the best square for the queen!   20.Qe3!  leaves Black without a move.  20...Qb8  21.Nd5  is a disaster, and so it  20...Qf6  21.Nd5  because  21...Qxb2  22.Rd2  Qa3  23.Nb6!  not only threatens the rook on a8, but the discovered check on f7 as well! }
20... Qf6 21. Ne4 { Now  21.Nd5  Qxb2!  is quite a different picture. } 21...
Qxb2 22. Qxb2 Bxb2
{ Black has won a pawn but White's activity should more than suffice to make a draw. }
23. Nd6 Na5 24. Nxb7
{ Slowly drifting. I prefer  24.Bxf7+  Rxf7  25.Nxf7  in order to force matters.  25...Kxf7  26.Rd7+  gives White enough activity to hold. After  25...Bxf3  26.Rd7  Bc6  27.Nxh6+  Kh8  28.Rc7  Bg7  29.Ree7  Bxh6  30.Rh7+  Kg8  31.Rxh6  Be8  Black is holding, but White is in no danger whatsoever. Even more, by pushing the kingside pawns this is an endgame where White can definitely play for a win. }
24... Nxb7 25. Bd5 Rab8 26. Re7 Nd6
{ 26...Nc5!?  was interesting as well. It is a pawn sacrifice, following  27.Rc7  Rbc8  28.Bxf7+  Kg7  29.Rxc8  Rxc8  and one, that allows Black to stabilize his position in order to get the queenside pawns rolling. White should of course hold, starting with  30.Bd5  but Black can certainly press here. }
27. Rd7
{ The engine prefers  27.Ra7  Rb6  28.h4  and sees no clear way for Black to make progress. It is always difficult to make that determination and I can understand Bok's desire to make a more forceful move. }
27... Nc8 28. Bb3
{ 28.Rb7  Rxb7  29.Bxb7  a5  30.Rb1  Bg7  31.Rxb5  Nd6  32.Rb6  Nxb7  33.Rxb7  is a forced line that I am sure both considered to be tricky for White after  33...Rc8  . The threat is a back-rank mate and if White prevents that, ...Rc2 picks up the a-pawn. In reality though, White makes a relatively easy draw with  34.g3  Rc2  35.a4  Rc4  36.Rb8+  Kh7  37.Rb7  when White's counterplay comes just in time. }
28... Kg7 29. h4 a5 { Now White really faces trouble. } 30. R1d2 Bf6 31. a3 a4
32. Ba2 Nb6 { Black has made major progress on the queenside. } 33. Rc7 Rbc8
34. Rb7 Rc1+ 35. Kh2 Nc4 36. Bxc4 bxc4
{ Now Black is just technically winning. The passed c-pawn, supported by the monster on f6 should bring it home. }
37. g4 c3 38. Rd6 c2
{ 38...Rf1!  threatening to queen the c-pawn while also attacking the f-pawn, would have won on the spot, but the game continuation is good enough as well. }
39. Rc6 Rd8
{ 39...Rb1!  40.Rbc7  c1=Q  is an excellent exchange operation. Black wins because  41.Rxc1  Rxc1  42.Rxc1  Bb2  43.Rc2  Bxa3  44.Ra2  is met with a check:  44...Bd6+!  Sometimes, for a sequence of moves to work, it can be a small detail like the king being placed on h2. If the king were on g2, White would have gotten the time to take on a4. }
40. g5 hxg5 41. Nxg5
{ This move is wrong on both a practical and an objective level.   41.hxg5!?  is certainly better, in order to keep more pieces on the board and make Black's technical task more difficult. }
41... Bxg5 42. hxg5 Rd5
{ 42...Rd2!  is a very smart way to essentially win a full tempo. After  43.Kg2  Rd5  44.Rbc7  Black can now take on g5 with check! A huge difference with the game continuation. }
43. Rb2
{ 43.Rbc7  Rxg5  44.Rxc2  Rcg1  should also be technically winning for Black. }
43... Ra1 44. Rbxc2 Rxa3
{ It was essential to go for the g-pawn. The a-pawn does not run away and will remain a weakness. }
45. f4
{ The big difference. White's f- and g-pawns cage Black's king and give White counterplay on the kingside. }
45... Rb3
{ 45...Rdd3  46.Rf6  Rh3+  and now not  47.Kg2  Rag3+!  48.Kf2  Rxg5!  , which is a nasty trick to avoid. After  49.fxg5  Rh2+  , Black has won a second pawn. But White can play instead, @@StartFEN@@8/5pk1/5Rp1/6P1/p4P2/r6r/2R4K/8 w - - 3 47@@EndFEN@@  47.Kg1  Rag3+  48.Rg2!  which doesn't change much. White is holding. }
46. R6c5
{ Losing the plot!   46.Ra6!  Rd4  47.Rf2  a3  48.Ra7  is the drawing setup. There is no way for Black to make progress here. }
46... Rd4 47. Rf2 a3
{ Gives White the chance to rectify the previous damage done.   47...Rbb4!  48.Kg3  a3  Prepares to place the b4-rook behind the passed pawn, which is a huge positional achievement. }
48. Ra5 Rb2
{ Black's last chance lays in  48...f5!  when Black may still be winning. The idea is shown in the following line:  49.Kg2  Rb2  50.Rxa3  Rxf2+  51.Kxf2  Rxf4+  and ...Rf4-g4 next, wins a second pawn. }
49. Rxb2 axb2 50. Rb5 Rd2+ 51. Kg3 Kf8 52. Rb7
{ Now the game is drawn, but Timman keeps probing, and in the end, almost managed to win. }
52... Ke8
{ The king runs towards the rook first, in order to run towards the b-pawn afterward. }
53. f5 gxf5 54. Kf4 Kd8 55. Kxf5 Kc8 56. Rb3 Kd7 57. Kf6 Rf2+ 58. Kg7 Ke6 59.
Rb5
{ Black has no clear winning plan in this position, but there is one trick left! }
59... Kd6 60. Kf8 Kc6 61. Rb3 Kd5 62. Kg7 Kd4 63. Kg8 Ke4 64. Kg7 Ke5 65. Rb5+
Ke6 66. Rb3 { A check, with  66.Rb6+  would have avoided what comes next. }
66... f5
{ A shocker!  67.gxf6  Rg2+  followed by ...Kxf6 is a clean win for Black. }
67. g6 f4
{ Suddenly, it is very sharp with 3 passed pawns being pushed all over the board! Time trouble also started to influence the play at this point.  68.Rb6+  followed by Kf7 still makes a draw. }
68. Kf8 Rc2
{ Now White is busted!  69.g7  Rc8  is mate, making Black win valuable time. }
69. Rb8
{ Instead,  69.Rb6+  Kf5  70.g7  f3  71.g8=Q  Rc8+  72.Kf7  Rxg8  73.Kxg8  f2  promotes either the b- or the f-pawn. }
69... Rc8+ 70. Rxc8 b1=Q 71. g7
{ White is still fighting with the g-pawn but the win is fairly straightforward for a world-class grandmaster like Timman. }
71... Qf5+ 72. Kg8 Qf7+ 73. Kh8 Qh5+ 74. Kg8
{ With the king blocking the passed pawn, Black has time to push forward. }
74... f3 75. Rf8 Qg4
{ 75...Ke5  76.Rf7  Qg4  is a win. Very pretty is the variation  77.Kh8  Qh3+  78.Kg8  Qe6!  79.Kf8  Qc8+  80.Ke7  Qg8  and wins. The g-pawn will fall next. }
76. Kh7 Qh5+ 77. Kg8 Ke7 78. Rf4 Qh3 79. Rf7+ Kd6 80. Rf6+ Ke5 81. Rf8 Qh5 82.
Rf7 Ke6
{ Here Bok sharply noticed that  83.Rf8!  now repeats the same position for the 3rd time and that caused him to stop the clock and claim the draw. An amazing escape! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Huschenbeth - l'Ami, Karlsruhe 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7 4. Nc3 Ng6 5. h4
{ No doubt the biggest test to the Cozio, and German Grandmaster Niclas Huschenbeth is known to never shy away from a principled fight! I have played Huschenbeth on three occasions and despite scoring just half a point, each game had some very interesting content which is why we started playing chess in the first place! }
5... Nd4
{ By now, this should come as no surprise. The knight move is the cornerstone of the course, making the whole line playable. }
6. Bc4 h5
{ And this is the novelty. When this game was played, I was already in the process of making this course and it is safe to say I have never been this well prepared for a game. }
7. Ng5
{ Niclas asks the critical question. Given that f7 is hanging and 7...Ne6 isn't very appealing, Black's position doesn't look very attractive. }
7... d5 { The move that changes everything. } 8. Bxd5 Nxh4
{ One of the most painful mistakes of my career! White's previous move is a big mistake after which Black is already close to winning. I was aware of all the lines, told myself not to rush things, and calmly double-check before executing the moves. Alas, something short-circuited in my brain when I made my move.  Having gone through the course, I hope you recall the right way to play here, which is  8...Bg4!  I will not repeat the analysis now but after  9.Bxf7+  Kd7  10.f3  Nxh4!  thedifference with the game becomes immediately apparent. }
9. Bxf7+ Kd7 10. d3
{ I made a joke to myself somewhere around this point, that it would have been nice to have gone through the moves with the move trainer. It is unlikely I would have mixed up the moves in that case! I'm completely lost here, though I pride myself in still managing to continue the fight - to some extent. }
10... Nxg2+ 11. Kf1 Nf4 12. Bxf4 exf4 13. Rxh5 Rxh5 14. Qxh5 c6
{ Taking away some squares from White's pieces and hoping to set up some tactics connected to ...Kd7-c7 and ...Qd8xg5, followed by ...Bc8-h3 and a check on f3 to win back the queen. It's wishful thinking, obviously. }
15. Qg4+ Kc7 16. Qxf4+ Bd6 17. e5 Be7 18. e6+ Qd6 19. Qxd6+ Kxd6 20. Nce4+ Ke5
{ I had some faint hopes here of regaining the e-pawn and suffering my way to a draw in a pawn down endgame. }
21. Kg2 Kf5 22. Rh1 b6
{ My idea was that after  23.Rh5  g6  24.Rh8  I have  24...Bb7  and I am still kicking.   22...Bxe6  was a better way to keep the game going. Though  23.Nxe6  Nxe6  24.Bxe6+  Kxe6  isn't a pretty endgame. }
23. Nf3
{ It turns out that even without queens on the board, the king can still get into trouble. }
23... Nxe6
{ 23...Nxf3  24.Kxf3  Bxe6  25.Rh5+  g5  26.Bxe6+  Kxe6  27.Nxg5+  is an endgame that is very easy to convert. }
24. Rh5+ g5 25. Nh4+ Kf4 26. Ng6+ Kg4 27. Rh8
{ Everything is falling apart, not surprisingly! } 27... Nf4+ 28. Nxf4 Kxf4 29.
Be6 Bb7 30. Rh7 Re8 31. Bd7
{ I resigned as material is about to get lost. Not a game I look back upon with fun memories but let it serve as an important reminder: use the move trainer before playing this line! }
